<TABLE ALIGN=CENTER>
<tr>
<TH></TH>
<td>
<FONT SIZE=+1>BOOKS, ARTS & MANNERS</FONT>
<P><blockquote>
What do Franklin, Jefferson, and Washington have in common with Haydn, Mozart, and Beethoven? <b>Balint Vazsonyi</b> knows, but the New York Philharmonic has forgotten....R. Emmett Tyrrell, Jr.'s <I>Boy Clinton</I> is  un flattering to the President-to put it mildly, remarks <b>John Coyne</b>....In <I>The Seduction of Hillary Rodham</I>, says <b>Rich Lowry</b>, David Brock bends over so far backward to be fair that he ends up fallling at his subject's feet....Despite the title of Thomas C. Reeves's <I>The Empty Church: The Suicide of Liberal Christianity</I>, the liberal churches aren't empty- yet, says <b>William Murchison</b>....After reading John Shelton Reed's <I>Glorious Battle: The Cultural Politics of Victorian Anglo-Catholicism</I>, Linda Bridges reflects that turmoil in the Anglican Communion is nothing new....<b>John Simon</b> performs an autopsy on the critical hysteria surrounding <I>The English Patient</I>....On the occasion of <I>NR</I>'s move from 150 East 35th Street to 215 Lexington Avenue, <b>Linda Bridges</b> decks these halls with fond memories.
</blockquote>
<P>
<blockquote>
<B><I>Misanthrope's Corner</I></B><br>
In the spirit of the holidays, <b>Florence King</b> distibutes micellaneous misanthropy.
</blockquote>
<P>
