<TITLE>Carolan & Keating</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="/sbsc/sbsmall.gif">
<P>
<center>
<h2>
Carolan & Keating - December 9, 1996<br>
Poor Over&#173;Worked and Under&#173;Paid State Legislators<BR>
<p>
</h2>
<h3>
by Matthew Carolan and Raymond J. Keating<BR>
</h3></center>
<P>
<br><blockquote>

Many of us apparently don't realize how grueling the job of a
New York state legislator really can be.  In recent weeks, some
legislators are telling anyone who will listen how &quot;stressful&quot;
and &quot;hectic&quot; their jobs are.  They pat themselves on
the back, and declare that they all &quot;work hard.&quot;  And
because they slave so arduously, these public servants plan to
give themselves a pay raise.
<P>
How reassuring.  We must have been deluded to think legislators
are lavishly compensated, while their efforts are wasteful and
incompetent.  
<P>
For example, it costs a little more than $1 million per office
to run the state senate and more than $500,000 per office for
the assembly.  These not insubstantial amounts pay for large staffs,
cars, public relations apparatuses, multiple offices, et al. 
Indeed, the New York state legislature employs more than 4,000
bureaucrats.  It must be very time consuming for legislators to
manipulate all these resources so that taxpayers fail to detect
the utter waste involved.  
<P>
And then, of course, there's all that pandering to whiners and
special interests.  Assemblyman Tony Seminerio of Queens reportedly
said he deserves a pay raise because he puts &quot;a lot of time
in&quot; and has &quot;a lot of responsibility.&quot;  Seminerio
was recently quoted: &quot;It's a quarter after five and I'm still
here.  I'm waiting for a constituent, who will probably be here
at 20 to six.  Tonight I have two meetings to go to.&quot;  How
does tired Tony do it?  After all, none of the rest of us have
ever worked all the way to 6:00 pm, and then had work commitments
later in the evening, right?  In addition, most of those evening
&quot;meetings&quot; for elected officials involve cocktails,
appetizers, dinner, and meeting people who will fill their campaign
coffers.  It must be brutal.  
<P>
One has to wonder why tired Tony and other complainers in the
state legislature don't flee the extreme pressures and low pay
of elected office and get a cushy private sector job.  Why come
back election after election, if things are so tough?  Instead,
they could do something real easy, like start a business; produce
a service or product people actually want; wrestle with onerous
state taxes, regulations and bureaucrats; and only work 18 hours
a day for six or seven days a week.  
<P>
Interestingly, some state legislators actually do have their own
businesses &#173;&#173; that is, if you can call being a law partner
having a business.  Wow, Superman stand aside!
<P>
These poor gals and guys in the legislature have not gotten a
raise since 1989.  Golly, how can they keep up with the rising
cost of living?  We suppose the fact that the job of state legislator
is a part&#173;time position is to be ignored.  Also, that New
York state legislators are the second highest paid in the nation,
only recently surpassed by California, must be set aside.  Additional
lulus (i.e., stipends) for most legislators, worth anywhere from
$6,500 up to $30,000 annually, awarded for doing their jobs and
staying in line politically, cannot be considered.  Expense reimbursements
for being in Albany, worth just under $100 per day on average,
must be pooh&#173;poohed as well.  
<P>
In addition, we should turn a deaf ear to an increase in state
legislator's base bay from $32,960 in 1984 to $57,500 today &#173;&#173;
when adjusted for inflation, a better than 15 percent increase.
 Add in the aforementioned lulus, and the average part&#173;time
state legislator garners about $70,000 per year.
<P>
Lastly, we assume that no link between pay and productivity should
be made at all.  Little lapses in job performance should be overlooked,
like chronically late budgets; high taxes; bloated, inefficient
and wasteful government; over&#173;regulation; state debt gimmicks,
led by off&#173;budget public authorities, designed to skirt the
State Constitution; and a government patronage mill.
<P>
If we ignore all these many factors, then New York state legislators
deserve a pay raise.  However, if we cannot overlook such lapses
&#173;&#173; for both ethical and economic reasons &#173;&#173;
then New York legislators deserve a massive pay cut.
<P>
Perhaps the time has come for serious reforms that will make the
New York state legislature a citizens' body, rather than a body
of lifetime politicians.  The framers of the State Constitution
had such a notion in mind when they required that a legislature
could not vote a pay raise for itself.  A pay raise can only take
effect for the next legislature.  Today, however, the next legislature
is largely the same as the current and previous legislatures.
<P>
Two reforms are needed.  First, require that all pay raises in
the state of New York, whether for state or any local elected
officials, pass muster with the voters before being implemented.
 Second, institute term limits in New York.  Eight years for both
legislators and the governor &#173;&#173; and why not local officials
as well &#173;&#173;  should be sufficient.
<P>
Not only would New York gain a true citizens' legislature, but
poor Tony Seminerio and his over&#173;worked legislative colleagues
would be released from their current back&#173;breaking duties.
 It's the least we can do for these suffering souls.
<P>
<hr>
<center>
<P><font size=-1>
Matthew Carolan is executive editor of National Review.  Raymond
J. Keating serves as chief economist for the Small Business Survival
Committee.  The views expressed are their own.  Copyright 1996.
 All rights reserved.<BR></font>
