<head>
<title>Carolyn and Keating</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="/sbsc/sbsmall.gif">
<p>
<center>
<h2>
Carolan & Keating -- October 14, 1996<br>
The Dying "Culture of Death"
<br>
</h2>
<p>
<h3>
by Matthew Carolan and Raymond J. Keating<br>
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<blockquote>

<p>It's ironic how destiny works.  Amidst all the hoopla in Albany over George Pataki's rather meager accomplishments, along with a dreary presidential campaign, a relatively unknown Attorney General by the name of Dennis Vacco quietly prepares to argue a case before the Supreme Court that will shake the republic, and make his a household name.
<p>The case is Quill v. Vacco, which the High Court has agreed to review after a Federal court struck down New York State's law against assisted suicide.  A decision will come early Summer.  No matter the outcome however, the case will mark the end of the culture of death.
<p>In the July 21 New York Times Sunday Magazine, the nation's foremost anti-euthanasia expert, Professor Yale Kamisar, expressed concerns that assisted suicide be seen as a privacy issue akin to that found in Roe v. Wade, which he supports.  Kamisar now wants limits on what one does with one's own body: "When the Court ruled in 1973, it termed abortion unique," the professor notes. "It never said the right of privacy should be extended this far."
<p>The Times reports that many pro-choicers are joining pro- lifers in a new anti-assisted-suicide coalition.  They argue that "pulling the plug," allowing someone to die from their own natural ailments, is not the same as intentionally killing them through lethal injection -- even if it is a "private" matter between a person and her doctor.
<p>We agree.  Who or what is the "cause of death" makes all the moral difference.  But Kamisar and friends are a little late.  When Dennis Vacco goes before the Supreme Court, he will be fighting seventy years of liberal jurisprudence -- which has deemed nearly every question of life and sexuality to be "religious" and therefore unconstitutional bases for the law.
<p>For example, in Hawaii, "marriage" is about to be redefined. Once linked to notions of heterosexuality, fidelity, and offspring, marriage is now an empty concept, to be defined according to one's constitutionally protected "liberty."  So too for "life," which the Casey decision says is another empty concept.  Mothers may define the "meaning" of the life of their child any way that want, and act accordingly.
<p>Now the new utopians say, "Why should we be bound by what Hippocrates said, when referring to both suicide and abortion he said: 'Doctors may not kill.'?"
<p>The chickens of privacy then have come home to roost.  Under the mantle of privacy, Americans have the right to be despairing lunkheads; to be shortsighted; to live life in terms of a false dilemma, and have doctors help them.  On abortion: "It's either my life, or this baby's, there is no other way."  On suicide: "Either I live in terrible pain, or somebody kills me (death with dignity), there is no other way."
<p>We do not agree with either murderous notion. As Hippocrates argued, there is always a middle way, and the doctor must find it.  Despite being armed with only a pestle and some herbs to ease pain, Hippocrates' had the more progressive vision, because he built medicine on metaphysics, which we have rejected.  He saw that doctors, as humans, not Gods, do not have the competence to determine the value of any life, but only to serve that life with pain relief, or healing.  It's ironic that with all our advanced skills for pain relief we demand the easier way.
<p>You can be sure however that our worried liberals will not invoke God before the Court, having already granted the humans god- like powers in Roe v. Wade and Casey.  They can only turn to their own self-interest, which may not be enough to stop the death march of liberty.  In the Netherlands, where assisted suicide is legal, doctors regularly kill people without their consent, because the law allows the doctor God-like judgement that some lives are objectively not worth living.
<p>If the Court strikes down state laws against assisted suicide, we expect a constitutional crisis undermining the judicially imposed culture of death.  Some governors are thought courageous enough to oppose the Court, like George Allen of Virginia, or Kirk Fordice of Mississippi.
<p>But even if the Court denies a broad right to assisted suicide, it is still a victory against the entire culture of death. For the Court would be implicitly accepting that medical tradition can have an objective nature against killing, against despair.  And from this small seed, new insights may grow.
<p>As psychiatrist Herbert Hendin told the Times about the desire for suicide, it is a "cry for help," and with proper care, the depression goes away.  Pain relief is always possible for the suicidal.  Then isn't the same relief, a fortiori, always possible for the depressed pregnant woman?
<p>Pray then, for Dennis Vacco. His job is nothing less than reversing the course of the established civil religion.
<p>
</pre>
Matthew Carolan is executive editor of National Review.  Raymond
J. Keating serves as chief economist for the Small Business Survival
Committee. The views expressed are their own.  Copyright 1996.
<p>
</blockquote>
