<html>
<head>
<title> Carolan & Keating - July 15, 1996</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<img src="/sbsc/sbsmall.gif">
<blockquote>
<p>
<center>
<h2>Carolan & Keating - July 15, 1996<br>
Olympic Fever in New York
</h2>
<p>
<h3>by Matthew Carolan and Raymond J. Keating</h3>
</center>
<p>
<dd>Like most everyone else, C&K is looking forward to the summer Olympics getting underway this week in Atlanta.  From baseball to gymnastics, fencing to sailing, skeet shooting to equestrian events, we'll watch as much of the games as we can, wearing our sports nationalism proudly.  C&K has caught Olympic fever. <p>
<dd>Recent reports illustrate that New York politicians are not immune to this fever either.  In fact, some of them are so excited they're planning to try to lure the Olympics, once more, to New York.  Previously, the winter games came to Lake Placid in both 1932 and 1980. <p>
<dd>Lake Placid is at it again.  The village's mayor, T. James Strack, recently announced that Lake Placid is considering a bid for the winter games of 2022.  Talk of competing for games so far off in the future is difficult to take seriously.  However, on June 26, The New York Times quoted Strack declaring: "Any good plan is a plan that is developed 25 to 30 years in advance."  We'll leave it to the future and our readers to decide whether Mayor Strack is a long-term visionary, or just an opportunistic politician looking to garner some short-term media attention. <p>
<dd>In the meantime, a more immediate effort has begun to bring the summer Olympics of 2008 to New York City.  No doubt, it's an exciting notion.  However, wild-eyed predictions are being made by various politicians and boosters in terms of the impact and costs of actually bringing the Olympics to the Big Apple.  We are told that tens of thousands of new jobs will be created at no cost to New York taxpayers.  Given Mayor Giuliani's similar predictions regarding a new government-built and owned stadium for the Yankees on Manhattan's west side, New Yorkers would be wise to be skeptical of such grand predictions. <p>
<dd>A sober assessment obviously is needed.  And we don't mean an assessment by a consulting firm paid for by the people in favor of the Olympics coming to New York City.  An independent assessment is required.  C&K humbly offers its services. <p>
<dd>First, it is crucial to understand that bringing the Olympics to New York City will in no way cure the city's economic ills.  The actual boost to the economy will be short-term in nature -- albeit probably a substantial economic blip, but a blip nonetheless.  Only deep tax cuts, regulatory relief, and government downsizing will cure New York City's economy, which has been in decline for decades. <p>
<dd>Second, if the games are funded through the private sector -- as is the attempt traditionally -- then whatever boost does occur will be real.  Extensive government involvement will only serve to tarnish the games -- creating numerous inefficiencies and boosting costs.  Fundamentally, private, voluntary funding is always far preferable to government taxation.  The market works far better than government bureaucrats. <p>
<dd>However,  just when New York City seeks the games, of course, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) seems on the verge of making government financial guarantees a part of the Olympics bidding process.  Preliminary cost estimates to bring the games to New York City in 2008 run in the neighborhood of $3.3 billion.  We wouldn't be surprised to see that number rise considerably.  In comparison, the Atlanta games will cost about $1.7 billion. <p>
<dd>One needs to remember that the 1984 games in Los Angeles were the first to actually make money.  The IOC obviously is seeking to protect itself from future losses through government guarantees.  In addition to the clear affront to New York's already overburdened taxpayers, consistent state and city fiscal troubles make such guarantees non-viable. <p>
<dd>In the end, we don't wish to play the part of party spoilers.  We believe New York City should pursue the 2008 Olympic summer games -- and even Lake Placid the winter games of 2022 -- with two provisions: 1) no taxpayer dollars or guarantees should be utilized, and 2) after the games, Olympic venues should be privatized.  After all, the state should be eliminating its Olympic Regional Development Authority, not expanding such a boondoggle. <p>
<dd>The summer Olympics of 2008 in the Big Apple, and the winter games of 2022 back in Lake Placid, are intoxicating ideas.  If taxpayers are not tapped, then C&K looks forward to helping the cause for bringing Olympic sailing contests to the waters around the Statue of Liberty, gold-medal baseball to Manhattan's west side, tennis to Flushing, and perhaps bobsledding and ice skating again to Lake Placid.  We've got tax-free Olympic fever.
<p>
_________________<br>
Matthew Carolan is executive editor of National Review.  Raymond J. Keating serves as chief economist for the Small Business Survival Committee.
<p><br>
