<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Keating's Corner</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><h2>
Keating's Corner</h2>
<P><br><b>
State Budget Politics: Republican vs. Republican
<p></b>
by Matthew Carolan and Raymond J. Keating	
<p>
<i>June 17, 1996</i>
<p><br>
<hr width="85%">
<p><br>
</center>
<blockquote>
Since coming aboard as New York State budget director in January 1995, Patricia Woodworth has been assailed by Democrats; public-employee unions and other special interests; State Senate Republicans; and some colleagues in the Pataki administration. Obviously she's doing something right.	An experienced and highly competent public servant, before coming to work for Governor Pataki, Patricia Woodworth helped bring fiscal sanity to the state budgets of Governor John Engler in Michigan and Robert Martinez in Florida.  Some tout her as a future budget director for a Republican White House. 	
<P>
Woodworth does not have to be in Albany, she doesn't need this particular job.  We're lucky to have her.  Still, many of our fine New York politicians criticize her as not knowing enough about New York's budget process.  Translation: Woodworth possesses no interest in the seedy, deal-making aspects of the State budget process, and, unlike many of her Republican colleagues, she is deadly serious about cutting the budget.	An assault on Woodworth by Democrats is to be expected. Democrats are at least principled in believing special-interest politics and bigger government are good things. However, State Senate Republicans, who talk about cutting government and taxes, and unleashing the private sector, exhibit little real interest in seeing that happen.  
<P>
They are hypocrites. And now, when the voters expect them to finally come through, they're turning against one of their own, and each other, much to the delight of the Democrats.	The Republican smear campaign against Patricia Woodworth is another instance of GOP pettiness and misogyny, along with the campaign against Betsy McCaughey Ross.  Our sources in Albany report wide acclaim for Woodworth as smart and savvy, who works extremely well with her staff of 350, and who, contrary to the whispers, is intensely loyal to the Governor.  She also has brought improvements to the state budget, which is far more readable now then ever before.  But, as one source told us, "When your the smartest kid in the class, people resent you."	State Republicans have run the state GOP for years like a private men's club.  Everybody is supposed to shut up and do what they're told.  When a woman who speaks her mind and sticks to her guns comes along, the cowards show their real colors and grumble to the media about  bitchy or flighty women.  	
<P>
State Senate cowards, who in this election year haven't the courage to stand up to the unions and other special interests that are strangling New  York taxpayers, also fail to stand up to Woodworth's boss George Pataki either.  So they attack an underling.  Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno sends out a press release calling for "restoration" of $1.2 billion to this years budget, while taking a swipe at the budget director.  His justification for the spending like: Well, it's less than last year's $1.5 billion.  And to think George Pataki dumped Ralph Marino for this guy.	Pataki has stayed above the fray and often seems remarkably dispassionate about a budget process that careens out of control.  But we won't pass final judgement on the Governor's budget performance until everything is finished.  While many pundits criticize the state for chronically late budgets, we're more concerned with the final product.  In the past, Senate Republicans forced late budgets by wrestling with Democrats as to how pork should be doled out.  Thus far, in the Pataki era, budget debates have been more substantive -- about tax cuts and real spending restraint. 
<p> 
If Pataki does not get a budget until July, but gains most of what he wants in terms of spending restraint and program reforms, he'll deserve high marks.  However, if he gets nothing out the current delay, then the Governor will deserve criticism.	In Michigan, Patricia Woodworth saw first-hand that standing by your principles and advancing a budget agenda of less spending and lower taxes is a political winner.  Michigan's John Engler withstood the assault from special interests, carried through with his ideas, and now is wildly popular.  Indeed, Engler may become Bob Dole's running mate for this coming November.	Confronted by big-spending Assembly Democrats and wet-fingered Senate Republicans, Pataki would be wise to give serious weight to the advice he receives from his budget director, while offering her more public support as well.
<P>
<br><center>
<i>Matthew Carolan is executive editor of National Review.  Raymond J. Keating serves as chief economist for the Small Business Survival Committee.</i>
<p><br>
| <a href="/sbsc/corner/corner.html">Keating's Corner</a> |</center>
