HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 02:58:38 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 27-Sep-96 19:06:30 GMT
Content-length: 5169
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Keating's Corner</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h2><center>
Keating's Corner</h2>
<P><br><b>
Public-Sector Unions and Privatization 
<p></b>
by Matthew Carolan and Raymond J. Keating
<p>
<i>April 29, 1996</i><p><br>
<hr width="85%">
<p><br>
</center>	
<blockquote>
We'd like to introduce the Carolan-Keating law of public policy.  It serves as a thumb-nail measure of how much support or opposition a public policy initiative deserves: If public-sector-union officials strongly oppose an initiative then it's worthy of support, and anything they support is worth opposing.	Public-sector unions thrive on big government.  The more taxpayer money government spends, the more jobs and influence for unions.  And since union membership is on the decline in the private sector, government serves as the last bastion of unions.  	
<P>
Therefore, sound public policy steps, like tax cuts, deregulation, school choice, and spending reductions, attract vehement opposition from public-sector unions.  In fact, as we have seen in New York in recent years, these unions often resort to hyperbolic television, radio, and newspaper scare ads.  	The issue riling unions most today is privatization.  Indeed, if you want to liven up the next cocktail party you're attending, find a public-sector-union official, mention privatization, and watch the sparks fly.  (We have, and it's great sport!)	Privatization means selling government-owned assets or shifting services completely out of the realm of government and into the private sector.  The taxpayers no longer possess any ties to the asset or service.  A step child to privatization is competitive contracting, whereby private enterprises regularly bid to provide services while taxpayers still foot the bill.  	
<P>
The benefits of privatization and competitive contracting are clear: 1) selling assets generates revenues that should be applied to debt retirement or rainy day funds, 2) shifting services completely to the private sector relieves taxpayers of the costs, and improves the quality of those services through competition and the profit motive, 3) in the case of pure privatization, government stops competing with private businesses, and 4) allowing companies to compete to provide services saves taxpayer dollars.	However, privatization has had a particularly rough time in New York, the number one union state in the country.  Almost 29 percent of all workers in New York are union members -- highest proportion in the nation and almost twice the national average.  	
<P>
Nonetheless, Governor Pataki at times musters the courage to utter the "p" word.  For example, the Governor has pushed for privatizing state-owned Stewart Airport.  Even New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani has tested the privatization waters by putting the U.N. Plaza Hotel up for sale.  And the New York-New Jersey Port Authority actually privatized its Vista Hotel in Manhattan for more than $140 million.  (That's right, government in New York owns and operates hotels!)	Activists Ron Lauder and Allen Roth deserve considerable credit for teaching the privatization gospel in New York.  Unfortunately, the Democrats express no interest in privatization -- unwilling to offend their union supporters -- and Republicans often forget their lessons.  For example, in complete contrast to the privatization movement, Governor Pataki supports a state takeover of the Long Island Lighting Company (LILCO)!	Much can and needs to be privatized at both the state and local levels in New York.  
<P>
Candidates for privatization are numerous, including public housing (sell it or even give it away), airports, horse race tracks, Off-Track Betting (patronage mill and retirement home for politicians), golf courses (New York State owns 18 with many more owned by counties, cities and towns), marinas, ski resorts (the state owns Gore and Whiteface Mountain ski centers), theaters, stadiums (don't build new stadiums for the Mets and Yankees, privatize Yankee and Shea Stadiums), buildings (how about the World Trade Center?), arenas (Nassau Coliseum -- home to the New York Islanders), mass transit services (buses, trains and subways), convention centers, hospitals, and prisons.  
<P>
Competitive contracting opportunities are widespread as well, such as operating state and local parks, trash pick up, road maintenance and snow removal, workfare programs, and more.  	Oh, and of course, after the state takes over LILCO, that too will be a candidate for privatization.	In addition to saving taxpayer dollars and improving services, very often workers find expanded opportunity through privatization that would not exist in a straightforward government job.  In fact, the only clear losers under privatization are the officials who sit atop public-sector unions.  Clear proof supporting the Carolan-Keating law of public policy.
<P>
<br><center>
<i>Matthew Carolan is executive editor of National Review.  Raymond J. Keating is chief economist with the Small Business Survival Committee.</i>
<p><br>
| <a href="/sbsc/corner/corner.html">Keating's Corner</a> |</center>
