<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Keating's Corner</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><h2>
Keating's Corner</h2>
<P><br><b>
Who Would a Flat Tax Hurt in NY -- the People or Politicians?
<p></b>
by Matthew Carolan and Raymond J. Keating
<p><i>March 11,1996</i>
<p><br>
<hr width="85%">
<P><br></center>
<blockquote>
	Under the iron hand of Senator Alfonse D'Amato, New York Republicans delivered the state's March 7 primary to Senator Bob Dole, and dealt a death blow to the now defunct presidential campaign of Steve Forbes.  Along the way, New York Republican leaders hurled slurs at Forbes' central campaign issue -- a 17% flat tax to replace our current federal income tax system.	Leading up to the primary, Senator D'Amato declared: "The flat tax will be devastating for New York," citing studies that pointed to a large drop in property values, especially on Long Island, due to the loss of state and local tax and mortgage interest deductions.  Governor George Pataki reportedly said that a Forbes-style flat tax would "destroy New York's economy."  Long Island Republican Congressman Peter King also railed against the flat tax.  Following their leaders, the pack of Republican anti-flat taxers in New York grew large.	
<P>
But the real reason New York politicos oppose a federal flat tax with few deductions was spelled out by New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani on the Sunday before New York's primary.  Giuliani bemoaned the fact that the elimination of deductions for state and local income and property taxes would hurt high-tax states and localities -- i.e., New York State and New York City -- and might even increase pressure to lower state and local tax rates.  Imagine the horror, New York politicians forced to lower tax rates!	New York elected officials like the fact that the current federal tax code subsidizes their own profligacy.  A system filled with loopholes also greases the wheels for deal-making and horse trading between New York's federal representatives and others from across the nation.  New York politicians have a clear stake in the current system.  However, New York taxpayers have a real stake in reforms that will cut their taxes and boost the economy.	
<P>
Under today's tax code, resources are drained away from productive private sector ventures and into largely unproductive government undertakings.  High tax rates create disincentives for working, saving, investing, and risk taking -- the true engines of economic growth and job creation.  Indeed, New York's burdensome tax structure has kept the state's rate of job growth well below the national average for at least the past two decades.  New Yorkers would benefit from a low flat tax in many ways: New Yorkers' tax rates would be cut significantly.  For example, under the Forbes plan, the top federal-state combined income tax rate in New York would fall from about 44 percent to 24 percent.  In New York City, the rate would decline from  more than 46 percent to about 28 percent.   Overall, according to the Heritage Foundation, the average household in New York would save $1,298 annually under a 17% flat tax. Under the current tax code, returns on investment are taxed at the corporate level and the individual level.  
<P>
As called for under the Forbes flat tax, double taxation of capital gains and dividends would come to an end, thereby boosting incentives for investment and entrepreneurship -- both in short supply in New York.  More investment and risk taking translates into faster growth and more jobs.   The Forbes plan calls for an end to deductions for interest payments at the business level and no taxation of interest earned at the individual level.  The effect of these changes, increasing supply and lowering demand for loanable funds, combined with lower tax rates, would be to dramatically reduce interest rates.   Lower interest rates, increased incentives for saving and investment, and faster economic growth -- all resulting from the flat tax -- will more than offset any potential downward pressure on property values due to a loss of mortgage interest and property tax deductions.  
<P>
Indeed, one could legitimately expect a tremendous boost to New York's economy, and therefore to property values, under a flat tax. And finally, if a flat tax actually does pressure state and local officials to cut taxes, so much the better.  In high-tax New York, any means to reducing taxes is a net plus for the state's economy and the well-being of individuals, families, and businesses.	Former New York Congressman and HUD Secretary Jack Kemp was so appalled by New York GOP machine attacks on the flat tax that he finally endorsed Steve Forbes for president.    Though Forbes soon dropped out of the race, Kemp's endorsement illustrated how principle and sound economics can rise above political pandering and special interests.	New York's economy would be helped, not hindered, by the flat tax.  And now that Forbes is out of the race, Senator Dole even has uttered a few niceties about the flat tax.  Unfortunately, with Senator D'Amato and New York's special interests at Dole's side, don't expect much movement toward a true, low flat tax in the near future.
<P><br>
<center>
<i>Matthew Carolan is executive editor at National Review.  Raymond J. Keating is chief economist with the Small Business Survival Committee.</i>
<p><br>
| <a href="/sbsc/corner/corner.html">Keating's Corner</a> |</center>
