<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Keating's Corner</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><h2>
Keating's Corner<br>
</h2>
<P><b>
The Shape of the Right in NY
<p></B>
by Matthew Carolan and Raymond J. Keating
<p><i>March 11, 1996</i>
<P><br></center>
<hr width="85%">
<p><br>
<blockquote>
"If the trumpet gives an uncertain sound, who shall prepare himself to the battle?" (1 Corinthians, 14:8)	With a major victory over Mario Cuomo in 1994 and a state Democratic Party in continuing confusion, New York conservatives are understandably looking forward to November's battle for control of the State Assembly.  But are they up to the task?  Herewith, some analysis: The Conservative Party is running television ads for a Gingrich-style "Contract with New York."  The strategy is the same as it was for the national Republican Contract with America: unite all the candidates around popular policies, focusing the races on a larger vision, in this case, a statewide vision.  The vision thing always has been unfamiliar ground to the New York GOP, so conservatives must provide a clear map.	The Contract contains some excellent policy prescriptions: term limits, school vouchers, initiative and referendum, an end to affirmative action, etc.  It sets a standard for smaller government and more freedom.
<P>
	Though, from an artistic standpoint, the Contract's television ad doesn't score very high.  It features tax-dollars being flushed down a toilet.  Undoubtedly true, but a point crudely made. The Contract will serve, we hope, as a precedent.  An objective standard to which local Conservative Party chairmen can be held accountable.  Some local chairmen suffer from a curious ailment of endorsing liberal Democrats.  Just to note the most egregious cases, we've discovered four assembly Democrats endorsed by conservatives at the local level who scored at 50% or below when their voting records were ranked by the state Conservative Party -- Dov Hikind, 35%; Steven Kaufman, 45%; Ronald Tocci, 45%; and Paul Tokasz, 50%.	Democratic Congressman Mike McNulty, also endorsed by his local Conservative Party, had an American Conservative Union 1995 rating of just 21%!  
<P>
Following the laws of probability you can get a monkey to vote more conservative.  Indeed, one Republican operative we spoke with after a statewide race a few years ago, observed that some local conservative politicos were more enamored of patronage than even their GOP confreres. While the Contract might help bring these strays back into the fold, it is not devoid of problems either.	For example, the tax proposal calls for a "middle class tax cut."  Why middle-class taxes only?  Is class warfare so ingrained in the minds of average New Yorkers that even the Conservative Party has to soft-pedal its message?  It makes sense to cut taxes across the board, in order to spur investment, entrepreneurship and job creation.  To boost New York's economy, we need tax cuts that are deep and provide real relief for individuals of all income levels as well as businesses.
<p>	
There's also the issue of abortion. Not even a word about restrictions appears in the Contract.  New York Christian Coalition executive director Jeff Baran finds it curious: "Compared to the Conservative Party's platform planks, you don't see any social issues in the Contract with New York." Baran told C&K that since the election of George Pataki, he sees a real move toward economic issues and away from social issues among state conservatives, which leaves his members feeling out in the cold.  It remains hard to get them excited about green eyeshade stuff, no matter how true.	Baran has "taken a lot of heat," he says, from his own people for "broadening" his agenda to economic issues, while not seeing any action on the social issues front in return.  This is a microcosm of what's happening at the national level, where alienated evangelicals have flocked to the Buchanan campaign, with its dismal economic message. 
<P>
As for the state legislative races, how is the current crop of Republican assembly hopefuls you ask?  What crop?  The GOP is off to a very slow start finding good conservative candidates.  This worries Dusty Rhodes, of the conservative group Change-NY: "We can't work with the GOP to get something done in this state, in particular to ensure that taxes aren't increased, if they don't get the right candidates to work with."	As is the case nationally, on the brink of real victory, New York conservatives seem strangely in disarray.  They struggle to unite social and economic conservatives, where in the past this was never such a herculean task.
<P>
<center>
<i>Matthew Carolan is executive editor of National Review.  Raymond J. Keating is chief economist of the Small Business Survival Committee.</i>
<p><br>
| <a href="/sbsc/corner/corner.html">Keating's Corner</a> |</center>
