Senators</a>
<li><a href="#contract">The <i>Contract With America</i></a>
</ul><p>
<hr>
<p>
<center>
<a name="for"><b>FOREWORD</b></a><br>
<a href="#contents"><font size="-1">(contents)</a></font><p>
</center>
     Every  small businessperson knows that a <i>Contract</i> is more than a promise.  It is an
agreement initiated by faith, but
enforced by law.  Each party can proceed  with confidence that the terms of the <i>Contract</i>
will be carried through, or the
negligent party will be forced to account for his or her actions.<p>

     That is why small businesses should be excited about the <i>Contract With America</i>.  Not
only does the <i>Contract</i>
represent a leap forward for small business interests, but it also represents a new thinking in
Washington.<p>

     The Republicans who signed the <i>Contract</i>  signed a business deal with the American
people.  In exchange for the
voters' support at the polls, we pledged to carry forth the terms of the <i>Contract</i>.  The
voters upheld their end of the bargain,
and now it is our turn.<p>

     In this pamphlet you will find an analysis of the positive impact the <i>Contract</i> will have
on small businesses.  By
the end of the first 100 days, the House of Representatives will have brought up and voted on
bills to lower taxes, reduce
regulation, reduce federal spending, provide real incentives for growth and reform the rules of
the House to provide
accountability.  Members of Congress will act in a more business-like way ourselves, and will
provide necessary relief for
the job-creating small businesses of our country.<p>



     And the <i>Contract</i> is only the beginning.  The new Republican Leadership in Congress
has pledged to reverse the big government trends of the last 40 years, and I am committed to the
goal.  As Chairman of the Small Business Survival Caucus, you can count on me to make sure
your voice as an entrepreneur is heard.<p>
 
Bill Zeliff<br>
Chairman, Small Business Survival Caucus<p>
<hr><p> 
 
<center>
<a name="intro"><b>THE CONTRACT WITH AMERICA AND SMALL BUSINESS</a></b><br>
<a href="#contents"><font size="-1">(contents)</a></font><br></center>     <br>

     The first 100 days of the 104th Congress will indeed be busy on Capitol Hill.  The
Republicans in the U.S. House of Representatives made a promise to the American people, if
elected to majority status.  They signed a "<i>Contract</i>" stating they would bring to the floor
of the House a series of ten bills representing a stark ideological alternative to the tax, regulate,
waste and spend Washington of the "old regime."<p>
      The Republicans got their majority wish, and now hundreds of thousands of small businesses
and entrepreneurs are curious about <i>The Contract With America</i> and how the specific
legislation will impact their livelihood.<p>
      The <i>Contract: A Small Business Guide to the First 100 Days of the New
Congress</i>, details the legislative initiatives within the <i>Contract</i>.  From tax cuts to
regulatory relief, the guide examines components of the <i>Contract</i>, specifically targeting
issues  of concern to small businesses. Because owners of smaller enterprises are
overwhelmingly concerned about fiscal  accountability in government, elements of the
<i>Contract</i> addressing those issues are also examined.<p>

     The last section of the guide to the <i>Contract</i> features each of the tens bills in the
<i>Contract With America</i>.  The Small Business Survival Committee strongly recommends
that you contact the Republican Conference at (202)-225-5107 if you have questions regarding
points in the <i>Contract</i> not addressed in this publication. The purpose of this publication is
not to diminish the importance of other <i>Contract</i>  points, but to highlight important policy
changes  that will directly impact your business and the economy.<p>

     Most delightfully, on the first day of the 104th Congress (January 4, 1995), the Republican
majority voted on and passed legislation forcing Congress to live under the same laws as every
other American and business.  Hopefully this measure will expedite action by the Congress to
roll back the burdensome regulations and laws that are impeding economic growth, and
unnecessarily costing small businesses billions in wasted time and money.  The Small Business
Survival Committee remains hopeful that the second 100 days of Congress will include a
"rollback process" to abolish illogical, outdated and excessive laws.<p>

     The <i>Contract</i>, by our analysis, is a good start at lifting government-imposed burdens
that are unnecessarily suffocating the backbone of the American economy -- small business.<p>
<hr>
<p>
<center>                  
<b><a name="open">OPENING DAY OF THE 104TH CONGRESS:</a></b>
 A Check List<br><a href="#contents"><font size="-1">(contents)</a></font><p>
</center>
On January 4, 1995, the first day of the 104th Congress, the Republican majority will
immediately pass the following major reforms:*<p> 
(If you are following <i>The Contract With America</i> and want to keep your own "score
card" we have provided a box next to each initiative, to check off each item  as it is passed by
Congress.  <b>All eight items below  have been passed</b>.)<p>
<ul>
<li><i>First</i>, require all laws that apply to the rest of the country also apply equally to the
Congress;<br>
<li><i>Second</i>, select a major, independent auditing firm to conduct a comprehensive audit
of Congress for waste, fraud or abuse;<br> 
<li><i>Third</i>, cut the number of House committees, and cut committee staff by
one-third;<br>
<li><i>Fourth</i>, limit the terms of all committee chairs;<br>
<li><i>Fifth</i>, ban the casting of proxy votes in committee;<br>
<li><i>Sixth</i>, require committee meetings to be open to the public;<br>
<li><i>Seventh</i>, require a three-fifths majority to pass a tax increase;<br>
<li><i>Eighth</i>, guarantee an honest accounting of our Federal Budget by implementing
zero baseline budgeting.<p>
</ul>     <p>
 
<b>Congress Not To Be "Above the Law"</b>
<p>
     <b><i>First</b></i> -- Congress passes many laws that small businesses must abide by, while exempting
itself from these very same rules and regulations.  Beyond the issue of Congress placing itself
above the law, members of Congress do not personally experience the burdensome nature of such
unrealistic rules and regulations.  Making Congress live by the laws they pass may entirely
change the nature and number of laws it enacts.  Perhaps when Congress     begins running         
its offices and committees  under the same        rules as small         businesses, we  may detect a
movement to repeal those that are particularly burdensome.<p>
<blockquote><i>"Regulators found 15 would-be violations in the office.  Among these hazards were a 4-inch
tear in the carpet beneath my desk, and file cabinet drawers that could be opened two at a time,
creating a potential hazard not identified with clearly displayed warning signs.  If I were a
private-sector employer rather than a member of Congress, I would have been fined
$1,500.</i><br>
<b>--U.S. Representative John Boehner</b> (R-OH), commenting on the results of an OSHA inspection
he requested of his Capitol Hill office.<br>
<i>Professional Roofing Magazine</i> 8/94
</blockquote>
<p>
<br>
 <b>Congress to be Audited for Efficiency,
and To Run Leaner</b><p>
     
<b><i>Second and Third</i></b> -- Congress has a sloppy reputation for running its own
institution.  Scandals, slush funds, and secret meetings seem to abound on Capitol Hill.  Items
two and three on Congress' first day list focus on cleaning up Congress, while streamlining its
bureaucracy.<p>

The financial workings within the Congress will be audited by an outside firm to determine if accounting                     procedures and other financial aspects of managing Congress meet the same rigorous standards employed by the private sector.<p> 
<blockquote>
<i>We're talking about a small army: 7800 people in the House and 4000 in the Senate, a total of
almost 12,000 federal employees.  The cost to taxpayers, with salaries, benefits, office space, et
cetera, runs to about <b>a billon and a half dollars a year</b>.</i><br>
<b>Martin Gross</b><br>
<i>The Government Racket, Washington Waste A to Z</i>
</blockquote>
<p>
     Doing their part to stop wasteful spending on  House operations, the committee staffs will be
cut by one-third with a real reduction in the number of committees and subcommittees. 
Committee jurisdictions will be realigned  to reduce duplication, while promoting efficiency.  
Like small businesses, Congress will have to do the same through reorganization, fewer staff,
and a more targeted agenda.<p> 
 
<b>Committees More Open and Accountable</b>
<p>
      <b><i>Fourth, Fifth and Sixth</i></b> -- Committee Chairmanship means POWER in Congress. 
The <i>Contract</i> calls for a vote to limit the number of terms a Member can serve as head of
a committee, limiting the possibility for corruption and non-accountability, while bringing  fresh
leadership to the position.<p>

     Within the committees and subcommittees themselves, the rules will be changed so Members
cannot cast ballots by proxy (ghost) voting.<p>

     The important work that takes place within the committee will be required to be open to the
public -- no more closed door meetings while Members of Congress secretly plot to raise our
taxes or their salaries.  All media will have equal access to meetings.  Committee and
subcommittee meetings may only be closed if approved by a majority of the total committee
membership, and only in cases involving national security, law enforcement information and
personal privacy. <p>
 
<b>Real Budgets and Protecting Taxpayers</b>
<P>

     <b><i>Seventh and Eighth</i></b> -- The 1993 tax increase passed by just one vote in the United
States House of Representatives and Senate -- a one vote margin gave the American people and
small businesses the biggest tax increase in history.  The <i>Contract</i> proposes that a
three-fifths "supermajority" be instituted to pass future tax increases.<p>

     When reauthorizing government programs, the government doesn't start with zero as its
baseline -- it  begins with last year's spending levels, pads them with add-ons, and adjusts those numbers for inflation.<p>
                               
<blockquote><i>Only in Washington can people engage in Orwellian Newspeak and get away with it.  A
spending increase is really a cut.And $82 billion more in tax revenue is not really an increase at
all.</i><br> <b>Jim Miller</b>, Former director of the Office of Management and Budget<br>
<i>Fix the U.S. Budget!</i>, <i>Urgings of an "Abominable No-Man"</i><p>
</blockquote>
     The <i>Contract</i> guarantees truth-in-budgeting. Increases will not ever be counted as
"cuts."  A spending cut will be a real cut.             <p> 
<hr>
<p>
<center>
<b><a name="account"><CENTER>FISCAL RESPONSIBILITY</a></b></CENTER>
<a href="#contents"><font size="-1">(contents)</a></font></center><p>                                        
<blockquote><i>A balanced budget/tax limitation amendment and a legislative line-item veto to restore fiscal
responsibility    to an out-of-control Congress, requiring them to live under the same budget
restraints as families and businesses</i>.    -- <b><i>Contract</i> With America</b><p>
</blockquote>

     Resoundingly, the message of the November 1994 elections was about limiting the size and
scope of the government's role in the lives of Americans and businesses.  Particularly, Americans
are concerned about  national leaders not addressing the serious issue of the national debt, and
the political establishment mentality  that believes government has unlimited power to go after
taxpayer dollars to fund wasteful programs.  <i>The Fiscal Responsibility Act</i> proposes real reforms
when it comes  to managing our nation's finances, and limits the tax and spending impulses of
big government supporters.                                   <p>

In a post-election poll commissioned by the Small Business Survival Committee, the number one response given by small business owners when asked what the most critical issue is for Congress and President Clinton, was "cut government spending."   Controlling spending is the primary means to rein in the power of meddling bureaucrats, and
bring fiscal sanity back to Washington.   <p>

<blockquote><i>"I place economy among the first and most important virtues, and public debt as the greatest
of dangers... If we can prevent the government from wasting the labors of the people under the
pretense of caring for them, they will be happy."</i><br> <b>--Thomas Jefferson</b><p>
</blockquote>
<b>Ballanced Budget Amendment/Tax Limitation Amendment</b><p>
The majority of American families, individuals and small businesses balance their budgets --
often times struggling to make ends meet.  Small businesses --many operating on razor-thin
margins -- demand  that Congress be held similarly accountable, and spend hard-earned tax
dollars as if they were their own.<p>

     Unfortunately, the nation's $4.6 trillion debt and $14.4 trillion in unfunded liabilities is a true
testament to the failure of our national leaders in this regard.  And, while billions are wasted on
government programs which have  proven to be a failure (or simply fail to go away) taxpayer
"contributions" have gone up, up, and up.  The United States federal government has not
balanced its budget or ended the year in a surplus since 1969.<p>

     The U. S. Constitution has  been amended twenty-seven times, and the <i>Contract</i>
proposes it be amended again -- this time with a balanced budget amendment (BBA).
Specifically, the <i>Fiscal Responsibility Act</i> requires that total outlays for each fiscal year
not outstrip total receipts for the year.  The   BBA will go into effect in fiscal year 2002, or the
second fiscal year after it is ratified by the states, whichever is later.<p>

     The <i>Contract</i> BBA requires that the President propose, and the Congress deliver, a
yearly balanced-budget.  In the House and in the Senate three-fifths of the whole of each
chamber can vote to incur a deficit.  In cases of national security  and war, the balanced-budget
requirement  can be waived through the adoption of a  joint resolution by a majority of the
total membership of both the House and the Senate.  The President must also sign the
resolution.<p> 
      Tax increases must be approved by a three-fifths majority in each house -- more difficult to
achieve than a simple majority, to dig deeper into our pockets.<p>

     Most Americans know that the underlying problem with our country's messy fiscal affairs is
that Congress spends too much -- not that it taxes too little.  The balanced budget amendment,
joined with the tax-limitation provision, will indeed make our elected officials more accountable
to taxpayers.  The combined force of the two will ensure that Congress looks to spending cuts
first before raising the taxes of small business and all Americans.             <p>
     
<b>Line-Item Veto</b><p>
     Hidden within every appropriations bill is billions of dollars worth of pork barrel projects and
use-less government programs that only benefit narrow special interests.  Given the line-item
veto, the president would have authority  to strike these wasteful spending provisions in bills
passed by Congress.<p>

     The <i>Act</i> gives the president a permanent line-item veto to provide a check on the
extravagance of the Congress. Once the president strikes these items, the  cuts would  become
immediately effective, unless rejected by the Congress on an up-or-down vote. A rejection of the
cuts can be vetoed by the president, and a two-thirds vote by the Congress is needed to overturn
the veto. <p>
     
 <hr>
<center>
 <p>        
<B><a name="dream">THE AMERICAN DREAM RESTORATION ACT:</b><br></a>
<a href="#contents"><font size="-1">(contents)</a></font><p>      </center>  
<blockquote><i>A $500 per child tax credit, begin repeal of the marriage tax penalty, and creation of
American Dream Savings      Accounts to provide middle class tax relief.  -- <b><i>Contract</i>
With America</b></i>
</blockquote>
<p>
The <i>Contract</i> begins to chip away at the federal tax burden on families, while encouraging future savings by all individual.  <i>The American Dream Restoration Act</i> gives recognition to the fact that families and individuals know how to use their hard-earned dollars more productively than bureaucrats and politicians in Washington. <p> 
<blockquote><i>The average American family head will be forced to do 20 years' labor to pay taxes in his or
her lifetime</i><br>
<b>--James Bovard</b><br>
<i>Lost Rights</i><p>
</blockquote>
<b> $500 Per-Child Family Tax Credit</b><p>
More money in the hands of consumers and the productive economy is good for small
businesses and economic growth.  Some Washington "experts" dismiss the impact of tax relief
for families.  The real experts -- American families (many of whom own a small business) spend
more on taxes than food, shelter and clothing combined.<p>

Benefitting about 50 million families, the $500 per-child tax credit becomes effective in 1996. 
All families with incomes up to $200,000 are eligible.<p>

<b>Anti-Marriage Bias Reformed</b><p>

The 1993 tax package had the unfortunate impact of imposing higher taxes on married
couples than they would pay if single.  The Act begins to erase the bias toward married couples
by reforming the tax code. The proposal calls for up to $2 billion dollars in relief.<p>
     
<b>The American Dream Savings Account</b><p>

The U.S. tax code needs to encourage savings in America -- increased savings provides more
capital for investment in small businesses and the future of America.  The Act permits
individuals to contribute up to $2,000 into a special savings account.  An individual pays taxes
on the amount contributed, but not on amounts withdrawn, when utilized for:<p>
<ul>
<li>Post-secondary educational expenses for a spouse, child or the account holder.
<li>Medical costs, including the purchase of long term care insurance.
<li>Retirement income.
<li>A first-time home purchase.
 </ul><p>

<hr>
<center>
           <p>                   
<b> <a name="job">THE JOB CREATION AND WAGE ENHANCEMENT ACT</a></b><br>
<a href="#contents"><font size="-1">(contents)</a></font><br> <p>  
</center>
<blockquote>
<i>Small business incentives, capital gains cut and indexation, neutral cost recovery, risk
assessment/cost-benefit analysis, strengthening the Regulatory Flexibility Act and unfunded
mandate reform to create jobs and raise worker wages</i>.    -- <b><i>Contract</i> With
America</b>
</blockquote>
<p>
     Ask American small business what most threatens their survival, and the likely response is
either taxes, or regulations, or both. The U.S. government,  whose job it is to protect and preserve America's free enterprise system, has become a foe of the private-sector.                                   
 <p> 
<blockquote>
<i>The dissatisfaction with Washington that small business feels can't be exaggerated.  A
nationwide poll by he Small Business Survival Committee found two-thirds of owners and
employees believe the government is a serious obstacle to their pursuit of the American
Dream.</i><br>
<i>--The Wall Street Journal</i>, December 2, 1994<p>
</blockquote>
    <i> The Job Creation and Wage Enhancement Act</i> addresses two main areas --  taxes and
regulations -- where the combined burden  of both is slowly strangling productive entrepreneurial
activity.<p>
<b>Small Business Incentives</b><p>
Small business, and the entrepreneurial spirit that drives America, continues to be a constant
in America's economy -- past, present and future.  As corporations continue to downsize, and
more men and women in their productive earning years are forced to "retire," many of these
experienced workers are starting a business.<p>

The number of home-based businesses has sky-rocketed. The technological revolution has
totally changed the way America does business.  Nearly 40 million Americans now work in their
homes.  Because small business and entrepreneurs are the backbone of the American economy,
the <i>Contract</i> calls for specifics to "prime the pump" for small business growth.<p>

<i>     The Act:</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Clarifies the deduction for home-offices: where the office is essential to the user's
business, taxpayers who use their office on an exclusive and regular basis, and perform tasks in
the office that cannot be fulfilled elsewhere, will qualify for the deduction.<p>
<li>Expensing:  Small businesses would be able to deduct the first $25,000 invested in
equipment and inventory. <p>
<li>The Estate Tax Exemption:  increased from $600,000 to $750,000 to help small
businesses pass on a family-owned enterprise to the next generation.        <p>
</ul>
<b>Capital Gains Tax Cut</b><p>
Venture capital, whether raised from one's family and friends, or from professional investors,
remains a critical source of funding for entrepreneurial enterprises. <p>

     The <i>Contract</i> proposes a reduction in the capital gains tax rate from 28 percent to 19.8
percent by  providing for a    50-percent exclusion on capital gains income, and indexing the rate for    
inflation.              <p>
<blockquote>
<i>Combined with indexation, reducing the top capital gains tax rate to 19.8 percent could be the
most pro-growth step taken by the new Congress ... encouragement for private-sector investment
in small business needs to be enhanced.</i><br>
<b>--Ray Keating</b><br>
Economics Advisor, Small Business Survival Committee<br>
<i>Small Business Tax Watch 1995</i><p>
</blockquote>
     Opponents of the capital gains tax cut contend it is a tax break for the wealthy. Based on 1992
tax returns however, 56 percent of returns claiming capital gains were from incomes of $50,000
or less (including the gain.)<p>

     In order to undertake and/or expand a small business, one needs capital.  Without adequate
capital, new ideas and businesses either never  make it to the marketplace or they die a premature
death.  The capital gains tax cut would greatly strengthen incentives for investment and
entrepreneurship.<p>

<center>
<b>"GET GOVERNMENT OFF OUR BACKS" MAKING REGULATORS  ACCOUNTABLE<p></b>
</center>
     The impact of excessive government regulation on small businesses, individuals and the U.S.
economy is staggering. Respected           sources place        the yearly               regulatory          burden on the      
economy as high             as $400--$500 billion.           <p>

<blockquote>
<i>There are at least 3 million fewer jobs in the American economy today than would have
existed if the growth of regulation over the last twenty years had been slower and regulations
more efficiently designed.</i>                       <p>
<b>--William Laffer III</b>, Heritage Foundation<br>
<i>How Regulation is Destroying American Jobs,</i> February 1993<br>
</blockquote>
<p>
    Regulations <b>and</b> regulators are out of control.  In addition to the fact that there are
simply too many, regulators are not required to weigh the cost of proposed regulations. What is
usually measured is simply the utopian benefits.<p>

     The <i>Act</i> proposes a common-sense approach to the regulatory process including:
<p>
<ul>
<li><b> Cost-Benefit Analysis</b>:      A stringent requirement that regulatory agencies provide the
true economic and compliance costs of proposed regulations.  How much more will consumers
pay, how many jobs will be impacted, will the proposed regulation retard or lower wages, and is
small business growth jeopardized?<br>
<li><b>Risk Assessment:</b>   Federal agencies would
be required to assess the risk to human health and safety of each newly proposed regulation.<br>
<li><b>Peer  Review</b>:  An independent peer review panel would be established in each of
the agencies to accredit the assessment.  The most credible and best available scientific data
would be required.<br>
<li><b>Regulatory Budget</b>:  The bill requires that federal agencies issue an annual
summary to the American people forecasting the compliance cost of all regulations on the private
sector.  The projected cost will be capped below its present level, forcing agencies to become
more cost-conscious of the national regulatory burden,  slowing the tidal wave of new
regulations. <br>
<li><b>Paperwork Reduction Act and Regulatory Flexibility Act Strengthened:</b>  The
federal government would be required to reduce the annual paperwork burden on Americans by 5
percent annually.  The "Reg. Flex Act"--  a law already on the books to protect small businesses
from burdensome regulations, would be subjected to judicial review, meaning  that small
businesses can sue the government to enforce the law.<br>
<li><b>Regulatory Impact Analysis:</b>  Federal agencies would be required to complete a
full evaluation and appraisal in the drafting phase of a major rule (affecting more than 100 people
or costing more than $1 million.)  In addition to determining whether the proposed rule concurs or perhaps clashes with current law, the analysis will include cost-effectiveness, persons impacted, implementation cost, and other specific criteria.  Real justification would accompany new regulations.<br>
<li><b>"Citizens' Bill of Rights:"</b>  The  power of federal regulators              has increased       
   steadily over            the years with          many                    businesses                          fearing an 
                     investigation                  and/or                   inspection by              a federal agency.     
     The bill would                     require that federal inspectors read businesses and individuals
their rights when faced with a complaint for an infraction.  Under the "Bill of Rights" an
individual can refuse a warrantless search, be present at the time of inspection  and, among other
rights, be reimbursed for excessive  damages.<p>
<blockquote>
<i>Rich Savwoir, owner of US 1 Auto Part Store in Bethpage, New Jersey, faces a one-year
prison term and a $10, 1000 fine because he didn't post a sign stating that his store accepts waste
motor oil for recycling.  Savwoir says that on the day in question, the sign was down because a
window-washer was working on the store.  -- Reason Magzaine</i><br>
"Crimes Against Nature"<p>
</blockquote>
<li><b>Private Property Rights:</b>  The Environmental Protection Agency, acting under such
laws as the Endangered Species Act has eroded our constitutionally protected  private
property rights.  The Act compensates property owners for the fair market value of their property
(up to 10 percent) for any reduction in the value of the property caused by federal government
law.<br> 
<li><b>Taxpayer Debt Buydown: </b>The Act creates a mechanism for taxpayers to designate
up to 10 percent of their tax
liability to help pay off the national debt.  The Congress would be required to cut spending by the
amount requested by taxpayers in the "debt buydown."<br>   
<li><b>Unfunded Mandates:</b>  How much more do you pay in state or local taxes due to
mandates imposed on local governments from Washington?  Unfunded mandates cause state and
local governments to raise taxes and strip away their ability to provide good, traditional local
services.  The <i>Act</i> requires that the federal government determine the costs of present
unfunded mandates, and begins to ease this burdenon states and localities by requiring a
reduction in those levels.<p> 
</ul>
<blockquote>
<i>"Congress has proven that it can't balance the federal budget
and, through unfunded mandates, it is determined to ensure that states and cities can't balance
theirs either"</i><br>
<b>Steve Moore</b>, CATO Institute<br>
 <i>Government: America's #1 Growth Industry</i>
</blockquote>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<center>
<a name="legal"><b>THE COMMON SENSE LEGAL REFORM ACT:</b></a><br>
<a href="#contents"><font size="-1">(contents)</a></font><br>
</center>
<blockquote>
<i>"Loser pays" laws, reasonable limits on punitive damages and reform of product liability laws
to stem the endless tide of litigation.</i><br>
<b>-- <i>Contract</i> With America</b>
</blockquote>
<p>
While everyone is harmed by the abuse of our civil justice system (except, perhaps, the lawyers) 
small businesses are particularly hard hit.  A small business owner in any number of fields or
ventures can be put out of business overnight by becoming the target of even a questionable legal
claim.  Logic is thrown out the window in tort law.  It seems that if your business involves any
risk (which inherently it does) it's not a matter of when "it" will happen, but how much "it" will
cost.<p>
The <i>Contract</i> </i>begins to clean up the legal system  by providing a check on the
frivolous lawsuits and incredible settlements awarded by juries.<p>

<blockquote>
"Those who set the trends in law, just as tose who set the trends in government, are seeking zero
risks . . . The only way to accomplish zero risk is to develop zero products . . . At some point
reason and balance must be restored."<br>
<b>Larry Burkett</b><br>
<i> What Ever Happened To The American Dream</i><p>
</blockquote>

Elements of the <i>Act</i> that will help stem the tide of the litigation explosion include:<p>

<ul>
<li><b>Loser-Pays Rule:</b>  To discourage the pursuit of weak law suits, the <i>Contract</i>
proposes that the losing party in the law suit pay the attorney's fees of the winner. The amount,
however  is limited to the total cost of the loser's own legal fees.  The rule only applies to cases
in federal courts, but the states are encouraged to adopt the same kind of rules.   The rule
promotes settlement as opposed to litigation by requiring that claimants notify the other party
prior to filing of the suit.  This step should open the doors of communication prior to going to
court, thus allowing more conflicts to be settled informally rather than through expensive,
lengthy litigation.<p>

<li><b>Product Liability Reform: </b> The <i>Contract</i> legislation creates a nationwide
uniform product liability law for punitive damages, joint and several liability, and fault-based
liability for product sellers.  Currently, business  must deal with 50 different state laws on top of
federal law.  The bill requires that "clear and convincing evidence" be established by claimants to
prove harm was caused by malicious conduct.  If harm is proved, punitive damages  are restricted
to three times the actual harm.<p>
     
Joint liability for noneconomic injuries is abolished under the Act.  Defendants are also only
liable for their own share of the wrong.  This aspect of the <i>Contract</i> addresses the
"deep-pockets" issue.   Businesses that only sell products will also be protected.  Product sellers
will be liable only for the wrong generated by their own negligence.  Sellers would be held liable
for product errors when manufacturers lack funds for the settlement or can't be brought to
court.<p>

<li><b>Prior Notice: </b> Written notice must be given to the defendant at least thirty days
before a plaintiff can bring suit.  The notice must include specifics of the suit and what the
plaintiff is seeking in damages.<p>

<li><b>Checklist for Congress: </b>The laws created by Congress often create years of
expensive litigation.  Legislation that is drafted in a vacuum, or when Congress fails to deal with
the all-important specifics,  often end up in the courts and usually the Supreme Court. 
Committees drafting legislation will be given a check list of items (e.g.: will the law be
retroactive and will the law apply to the government) to help minimize the possibility of court
action.<p>

<li><b>Strike Suits:</b> The proliferation of class-action shareholder law suits is hitting small
and medium-size growth companies very hard. In this type of suit  attorneys sue the company
because the stock purchases did not "live up to expectations."  These claims are particularly
hurtful to job creation and economic growth.  The Act clamps down on attorneys and stock
buyers who abuse the system by making a full-time racket out of shareholder class-action suits. 
In addition to other meaningful reforms, claimants must prove that they were intentionally
misinformed.<p>

<li><b>Honesty in Evidence and Lawyer Accountability:  </b>So-called experts are used daily
in the courts to justify often absurd claims.  In the federal courts the Act would disallow
testimony based on "junk-science,"  and would not allow experts to receive contingency fees (the
judge may, however, waive this in some cases.)  The Act will encourage the states to require that
attorneys justify contingency fees.  Laws that penalize attorneys for willfully adding to the cost
of litigations will  be strengthened.<p>
</ul>
<center>
<hr>
<p>
<b><a name="conclusion">CONCLUSION</a>:</b><br>
<a href="#contents"><font size="-1">(contents)</a></font><br>
<p>
</center>
 The new Congress, and the agenda devised in <i>The Contract With America</i>, will certainly
make 1995 the "Year of Small Business."  Indeed, policy and legislative decisions for this year
will have a renewed focus on those segments of society representing the  backbone, and the
foundation, of American society and the economy -- small business tops the list.<p>

Powerful special interests, however, will fight to keep this agenda from passing Congress. 
Opponents of limited government will try to persuade the American people that wholesale chaos
will erupt if sizeable spending cuts are enacted, or if the Congress begins to strip away some of
the burdensome regulation that is choking free enterprise.     The Small Business Survival
Committee encourages you to contact your United States Representative and Senators and ask
them to be bold, and pass the components of <i>The Contract With America</i> outlined in this
pamphlet.  You can reach them at:<p>
<b>The Honorable (name)<br>             
U. S. Senate<br>                                   
Washington, D.C. 20510<br>
<p> 
The Honorable (name)<br> 
U.S. House of Representatives<br> 
Washington, D.C. 20515
<p> 
<i>or
call </i>
<br>
U.S. Capitol Switchboard (202) 224-3121</b><p>
<hr>
  <center>
<p>
<a name="contract"><b><i>CONTRACT WITH AMERICA</i></b></a><br>
<a href="#contents"><font size="-1">(contents)</a></font><br>
</center>  
<p>
     ...Thereafter, within the first 100 days of the 104th Congress, we shall bring to the House
Floor the following bills, each to be given full and open debate, each to be given a clear and fair
vote and each to be immediately available this day for public inspection and scrutiny.<p>
<ul>
<li><b>The Fiscal Responsibility Act: </b> A balanced budget/tax limitation amendment and a
legislative line-item veto to restore fiscal responsibility to an out-of-control Congress, requiring
them to live under the same budget constraints as families and businesses.<p>
<li><b>The Taking Back Our Streets Act:  </b>An anti-crime package including stronger
truth-in-sentencing, "good faith" exclusionary rule exemptions, effective death penalty
provisions, and cuts in social spending from this summer's "crime" bill to fund prison
construction and additional law enforcement to keep people secure in their neighborhoods and
kids safe in their schools.<p>
<li><b>The Personal Responsibility Act:</b> Discourage illegitimacy and teen pregnancy by
prohibiting welfare to minor mothers and denying increased AFDC for additional children while
on welfare, cut spending for welfare programs, and enact a tough two-years-and-out provision
with work requirements to promote individual responsibility.<p>
<li><b>The Family Reinforcement Act: </b>Child support enforcement, tax incentives for
adoption,  strengthening rights of parents in their children's education, stronger child
pornography laws, and an elderly dependent care tax credit to reinforce the central role of
families in American society.<p>
<li><b>The American Dream Restoration Act:</b>  A $500 per child tax credit, begin repeal of
the marriage tax penalty, and creation of American Dream Savings Accounts to provide middle
class tax relief.<p>
<li><b> The National Security Restoration Act:</b>  No U.S. troops under U.N. command and
restoration of the essential parts of our national security funding to strengthen our national
defense and maintain our credibility around the world.<p>
<li><b> The Senior Citizens Fairness Act:  </b>Raise the Social Security earnings limit which
currently forces seniors out of the work force, repeal the 1993 tax hikes on Social Security
benefits and provide tax incentives for private long-term care insurance to let Older Americans
keep more of what they have earned over the years.<p>
<li><b>The Job Creation and Wage Enhancement Act: </b> Small business incentives, capital
gains cut and indexation, neutral cost recovery, risk assessment/cost-benefit analysis,
strengthening the Regulatory Flexibility Act and unfunded mandate reform to create jobs and
raise worker wages.<p>
<li><b>The Common Sense Legal Reform Act: </b> "Loser pays" laws, reasonable limits on
punitive damages and reform of product liability laws to stem the endless tide of litigation.<p>
<li><b>The Citizen Legislature Act: </b> A first-ever vote on term limits to replace career
politicians with citizen legislators.<p>
</ul>
     Further, we will instruct the House Budget Committee to report to the floor and we will work
to enact additional budget savings, beyond the budget cuts specifically included in the legislation
described above, to ensure that the Federal budget deficit will be less than it would have been
without the enactment of these bills.<p>
<center>
For More Information Call:<br>
The Republican Conference<br>
(202)-225-5107<p>
</center>
<p>
