<TITLE> FDA Hazards </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="/sbsc/sbsmall.gif">
<P>
<CENTER><H2>FDA Hazards:
<P>
How FDA Red Tape Impacts<BR>
Entrepreneurs and the U.S. Economy </H2></CENTER>
<P>
<H3><CENTER>by Raymond J. Keating</H3>
Chief Economist with the Small Business Survival Foundation
and<BR>
Co-author of D.C. By The Numbers: A State of Failure
<P>
August 1995
<P>
<br>
<hr>
<b>Table of Contents</b>
</center>
<ul>
<li><a href="#one">Message From the President</a>
<li><a href="#two">Introduction</a>
<li><a href="#three">FDA History and Responsibilities</a>
<li><a href="#four">FDA vs. Entrepreneurs and Patients</a>
<li><a href="#five">FDA Restrictions</a>
<li><a href="#six">FDA Intrusions</a>
<li><a href="#seven">FDA Budget and Employees</a>
<li><a href="#eight">Incentives Problem</a>
<li><a href="#nine">Market-Based Reforms</a>
<li><a href="#ten">Still Tea Time at the FDA</a>
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<center>
<a name="one"><H3>Message from the President</H3></a></center><blockquote>
<P>
Long held in high regard by the American public, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) has 
managed to squander much of its goodwill in recent years.  The FDA -- wrapped in its own "red-tape 
reality" -- is now under scrutiny.  Democrats, Republicans, patient groups, as well as the industries micro-
managed by the agency, criticize the FDA for its inefficiency, bumbling bureaucracy, and cavalier attitude 
towards business and the American people.
<P>
Under Commissioner David Kessler's leadership, the FDA has become chief advocate for the "nanny 
state."  Centralized, government decision-making for medical consumers and practitioners is the rule of the 
day.  In 1992, Dr. Kessler declared: "If individual patients and doctors made medical decisions on their 
own behalf, then the rationale for the FDA would cease to exist."
<P>
The grand illusion that the government can effectively render personal decisions or highly technical 
determinations laid the foundation for the FDA's failures.  Indeed, the FDA's severe shortcomings, as 
outlined in the following pages, prove that the agency should cease to exist.
<P>
The Small Business Survival (SBS) Foundation continues to review each of the federal government 
agencies as to their impact on entrepreneurship and economic growth.  In terms of selecting an agency that 
drives high-paying jobs and growth industries overseas, the FDA tops the list.  As the FDA has made it 
more difficult to gain medical device and drug approvals, more and more companies flee for friendlier 
regulatory shores.  Lost investment opportunities, lost businesses, and lost jobs, make for a sad 
commentary on the FDA's lack of vision.
<P>
From entrepreneurial medical device firms to vitamin distributors and food companies, the FDA has made 
it known that it is at war with American business -- with consumer casualties mounting.  The new 
leadership in Congress is addressing the many tax and regulatory impediments to entrepreneurship.  Efforts 
are underway to reform and restrain the IRS, OSHA, EPA, and other agencies.  The FDA certainly should 
not be shielded from bold reforms.  In this booklet, SBS Foundation highlights not only the problems, but 
also offers common sense solutions to allow for America's great tradition of risk-taking and innovation to 
continue, while maintaining a check on public safety.
<P>
					<CENTER> Karen Kerrigan<BR>
					  President<BR>
					  SBS Foundation<BR></CENTER>
<P>
<hr>
<a name="two"><H3><CENTER>Introduction</CENTER></a></H3>
<P>
The U.S. federal government's alphabet soup of agencies -- including OSHA, EPA, IRS, FBI, ATF, and 
more -- seem to be coming under ever closer scrutiny in recent months.  These agencies are being 
examined in terms of their missions, tactics, strategies, budgets, and effects.
<P>
Included in this scrutinized soup bowl is the FDA, or the U.S. Food and Drug Administration.  The FDA 
has set the standard for a gridlocked, costly, and even deadly federal bureaucracy.  The agency has gained 
infamy for its ability to throw monkey wrenches into the machinations of some of the most dynamic 
industries of the late twentieth century, such as medical devices and pharmaceuticals.  Indeed, the FDA is 
slowing medical progress, hampering entrepreneurial enterprises, and destroying jobs due to regulatory 
obstacles and bureaucratic gridlock.
<P>
The agency operates under a system of perverse incentives.  First, it possesses a monopoly in terms of drug 
and medical device approvals.  Second, since the FDA suffers consequences when problems develop with 
an approved product, the agency has every incentive to prolong the approval process.    Of course, a 
lengthy and costly approval process generates its own costs in terms of lost businesses, jobs, and lives.  In 
addition, the FDA seems to be plagued by assumptions that afflict much of our society in the late twentieth 
century -- namely, that all risks can be ameliorated in life, and that only the massive costs and bloated 
bureaucracies of government can assure relative safety.
<P>
In the following pages, we shall briefly review the responsibilities of the FDA, the agency's tactics and 
strategies, its impact on America's entrepreneurs, the FDA's budget, and finally propose some much-
needed, market-based reforms.
<P>
<hr>
<a name="three"><H3><CENTER>FDA History and Responsibilities  </a></CENTER></H3>
<P>
The first major federal drug legislation was passed into law in 1906 -- the Pure Food and Drug Act.  It 
forbade false and misleading claims about drugs, holding manufacturers liable for adulterated and 
misbranded drugs.  The Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act of 1938 required that manufacturers notify the 
government before marketing a drug.  Companies had to test for safety, and if within 60 days the FDA did 
not disapprove based on those test results, the drug was marketable.  In 1962, new regulations shifted the 
FDA to a pre-market approval process.  In 1976, Congress formalized federal regulations regarding 
medical devices, and in 1990 codified FDA pre-market approval of all devices.
<P>
Today, the FDA carries a long list of responsibilities, summarized as: regulating drug, food, cosmetics, 
biological product, and medical device labeling; approving new drugs, biological products, and medical 
devices; setting drug, biological product and medical device manufacturing guidelines; and establishing 
safety and effectiveness standards for drugs, biological products, and medical devices.
<P>
<hr>
<H3><a name="four"><CENTER>FDA 
vs. 
Entrepreneurs 
and Patients</a> </CENTER> </H3>
<P>
As is the case with most regulatory agencies, the FDA seemed like a good idea at first, but it has grown 
into a massive, misguided undertaking.  The FDA has placed enormous burdens on food, pharmaceutical, 
and medical device enterprises -- discouraging investment and risk taking in some of America's leading 
industries.  The FDA seems more intent on exporting American ingenuity and entrepreneurship, rather than 
encouraging the production of U.S.-made drugs and medical devices.
<P>
Examples of the havoc being wrought by the FDA abound:<ul>
<P>
<li>In the August/September 1995 issue of Reason magazine, Rick Henderson reported that "the FDA's 
Center for Devices and Radiological Health takes more than three times longer to approve a Class III or 
'substantial risk' medical device (such life-saving products as heart valves or CAT scanners) than do the 
agency's counterparts in Europe."  What is the impact of such delays?  "In the past 10 months, reports a 
survey published in June by the Health Industry Manufacturers Association, 50 percent of the more than 
500 device makers surveyed had moved some clinical trials of new medical devices overseas; 56 percent 
refused to test new devices on Medicare patients; and 75 percent planned to move their trials to Europe."
<P>
<li>Thomas G. Donlan noted industry trends driven by the FDA's regulatory maze in the July 3, 1995 issue 
of Barron's: "The failure of U.S. regulation can ... be seen in the scrambles that have roiled the industry to 
put research and manufacturing offshore, to make partnerships with foreign drug firms and to merge and 
merge and merge again in an attempt to create firms that are large enough to weather all the risks of 
regulation."
<P>
Of course, market-driven mergers in an industry are by no means worrisome.  However, substantial 
industry changes being driven by regulatory costs should cause regulators and their supposed overseers -- 
i.e., elected officials -- to re-evaluate their regulatory activities.
<P>
<li>Robert Higgs, in a report for the Competitive Enterprise Institute, noted the hurdles companies face even 
when making improvements in already existing products or in their manufacturing processes: "Changes in 
the product or the manufacturing process, no matter how small, might cause the product to be consigned to 
an indefinite stay in preapproval purgatory.  FDA failed to differentiate between new devices and 
manufacturing changes for existing devices.  Manufacturers therefore had a reduced incentive to make the 
minor improvements that, cumulating over time, could greatly improve the performance of their products 
and the efficiency of their manufacturing operations."
<P>
<li>Higgs also reported that FDA policies and conduct have boosted costs for medical device firms 
considerably -- perhaps adding $10 million to $20 million to a firm's budget, as well as several additional 
years before a new device gets to the market.  Such costs greatly reduce venture capital investment in new 
and expanding enterprises making medical devices.  One can only speculate as to the total number of 
potentially life-saving innovations and inventions that fail to reach consumers because regulatory costs 
reduce potential returns to such an extent that capital simply dries up.<P>
Higgs noted that from 1989 to 1991, U.S. medical technology firms invested roughly the same amount 
abroad annually -- $321 million-$333 million.  "Then in 1992, when FDA abruptly made its enforcement 
and approval policies more onerous, capital outflow jumped more than 200 percent to $993 million."
<P>
<li>One also has to wonder whether large firms feel the FDA's battering as severely as smaller and start-up 
enterprises.  Rick Henderson asserts in Reason that large, established pharmaceutical companies have 
benefited from the FDA's regulatory maze.  New, smaller firms lack the resources, expertise, and patience 
to surf the FDA's regulatory tidal wave.  Hence, entrepreneurs wipe out -- the system results in fewer 
competitors for established firms.
<P>
<li>A 1993 report from the House Energy and Commerce Oversight and Investigations Subcommittee 
acknowledged the woes tied to the FDA's approval process for medical devices: "The situation is 
intolerable.  The backlog for pending device applications exceeds 1,100. ... The FDA's enforcement 
practices have demoralized and perplexed much of the medical device industry."
<P>
<li>In testimony before the House Joint Economic Committee Hearing on Technical Innovations in Health 
Care on June 24, 1994, Robert C. DeHaven of the American Electronics Association declared that the 
FDA's "inordinately slow" regulatory process was threatening "the global competitiveness" of the medical 
device industry -- a $70 billion industry with more than 11,000 companies.
<P>
<li>A recent American Electronics Association survey reportedly found that 40 percent of medical device 
firms reduced their number of U.S. employees because of FDA delays, 29 percent boosted investment in 
foreign operations, and 22 percent moved U.S. jobs out of the country. 
<P>
<li>FDA approval times have mounted.  For example, in 1988, it took an average of 78 days for the FDA to 
approve a product change (i.e., a 510-K application); by 1992, approval time had grown to an average of 
126 days.  This number further ballooned to 173 to 213 days by 1994.   These applications are supposed 
to be approved within 90 days, according to FDA guidelines.  
<p>	
Approvals of new devices take anywhere from 437 to 840 days. New device approvals, however, are 
supposed to be completed within 180 days.
<P>
Meanwhile, the median approval time for generic drug applications stretched out from 12 months to 38 
months between 1986 and 1993.  Of course, these numbers exclude FDA requirements placed on firms 
that extend development time.
<P>
<li>The overall time it takes for a drug company to create, develop, and gain approval for a drug almost 
doubled from the 1960s to the 1990s, from an average of 8.1 years to 15 years.
<P>
<li>When compared with many other nations, a clear lag in drug approval in the United States exists.  For 
example, from 1985 through 1993, just 27 percent of the FDA's new drug approvals received their first 
marketing approval in the U.S.  Between 1982 and mid-1992, 82 percent of new biopharmaceutical drugs 
originated in the U.S., 14 percent in Europe, and 4 percent in Japan; 86 percent were first tested in the U.S. 
and 14 percent in Europe; yet, only 25 percent were first marketed in the U.S. and 75 percent in Europe.  
Of all drugs approved in the U.S., 12 percent had been available in foreign markets for 6-10 years, and 
another 9 percent were available for more than a decade.  In the area of psychotropic drugs (drugs 
treating mental ills), 17 percent were available in foreign markets for 6-10 years prior to U.S. availability, 
with another 17 percent for more than a decade.
<P>
These approval lags do not seem to necessarily translate into enhanced safety.  For example, Great Britain 
gets drugs to market quicker than the U.S., yet safety discontinuations as a percentage of total new drug 
introductions were similar in each country -- 4 percent in Great Britain and 3 percent in the U.S.
<P>
<li>A February 10, 1993 Wall Street Journal editorial ("Kessler's Devices") explained 1992's sharp increase 
in medical devise approval times this way: "The onset of these delays is no accident: they coincide with the 
aftermath of the Kessler-Congress jihad against breast implants.  With that searing event, word went out to 
FDA reviewers that all devices were to get new scrutiny.  John Dingell added to the fear by inviting some 
agency bureaucrats to visit his re-education camp on Capitol Hill.  Reviewers naturally began to ask more 
questions, demand more data and stonewall applications.  The resulting gridlock has been industrywide, 
affecting everything from catheters to imaging products for advanced surgery, tissue forceps, surgical 
staplers, lasers, and so on."
<P>
Of course, it was subsequently reported that several studies failed to show any link between silicone breast 
implants and various ailments that had been attributed to them by the FDA and a host of contingency-fee 
lawyers.
<P>
<li>The FDA continues to be embroiled in a controversy over the approval of Ambu International Inc.'s 
cardiopump, designed to help revive patients in cardiac arrest.  It has been approved and is on the market in 
many other countries including Canada, Great Britain, and France -- while ambulances in Austria are 
required to carry the pump.  
<P>
<li>In 1990, as The Wall Street Journal's Brent Bowers reported (May 18, 1993), the FDA notified the 
McCurdy Fish Co. in Lubec, Maine -- reportedly the lone U.S. company in the smoked-herring industry -- 
that it would have to significantly alter its process for producing smoked herring.  Since the turn of the 
century, the company had eviscerated the fish after the salting and smoking process; now the FDA 
demanded evisceration before salting and smoking.  Never mind that in the 20 years that John McCurdy 
ran the company -- producing three million pounds or 54 million filets of herring -- there was not one 
reported case of food poisoning.  McCurdy could not afford to buy the new equipment -- the business 
closed and Lubec, Maine lost 22 jobs.
<P>
<li>For almost the past decade, H. Earl Wright has been wrestling with the FDA over his Sensor Pad, 
designed to aid women with breast self-examination.  The pad has long been approved for sale in European 
and Asian nations.
<P>
<li>The Wall Street Journal reported on April 12, 1994 that one company -- International Rehabilitative 
Sciences Inc. -- already had FDA approval for its muscle stimulators, but since the company does business 
as RS Medical, it sought clearance a second time in 1990 in order to clarify ownership.  The FDA denied 
the application and rescinded its original approval.  Believing it was mistreated, the company decided to 
test the FDA's process by re-applying and having its consulting firm apply as well.  RS Medical was denied 
approval while the consulting firm received approval.  RS Medical took the FDA to court and won.
<P>
<li>The chief executive of the Minnesota-based Minntech Corp., Louis Cosentino, best summed up the effect 
of the FDA on entrepreneurs and the U.S. economy: "The attitude of the FDA is so antibusiness and so 
negative at this point that any prudent CEO has to be looking outside the U.S. as a safe haven."  Minntech 
laid off 50 Minnesota employees while expanding in Europe.
<P></ul>
Meanwhile, the so-called benefits for consumers from all these added delays and costs remain difficult to 
detect.  In fact, bureaucratic delays by the FDA apparently cost thousands of lives annually, as products 
and treatments are being denied to American consumers.
<P>
<hr>
<H3><a name="five"><CENTER>Export Restrictions</CENTER></a>  </H3>
<P>
The FDA erects barriers to the export of U.S. medical products as well.  Even if a product has been 
approved for use in a foreign country, the FDA generally does not allow for exportation to that nation if the 
product has not received FDA approval.  Again, in the case of medical devices, a lengthy FDA approval 
process is needed in order to export.  
<P>
The CEO of a medical device company was denied permission to export by the FDA -- so he moved the 
company from the U.S. to Switzerland.  The CEO observed: "The FDA denied us permission to export. ... 
So we had to export our manufacturing plant." 
<P>
<hr>
<H3><a name="six"><CENTER>FDA Intrusions</CENTER></a></H3>
<P>
However, the FDA does not stop at mere incompetence and bureaucratic gridlock.  In the 1990s, under the 
guidance of FDA Commissioner David Kessler, the FDA's enforcement efforts have become increasingly 
aggressive and intrusive.
<P>
Reports abound of the FDA's confrontational methods under Dr. Kessler's reign.  For example:<ul>
<P>
<li>In the May 1995 issue of Reason magazine, analyst Alexander Volokh reported: "Since 1990, when 
David Kessler took over as FDA commissioner, enforcement has been one of the FDA's top priorities.  In 
his first two months, Kessler added 100 new criminal investigators to his enforcement staff, many of them 
formerly with the Secret Service and Drug Enforcement Administration.  Armed raids on alternative health 
clinics and dietary supplement dealers followed, as well as increased warning letters, product seizures, and 
criminal prosecutions in the drug and device industries."
<P>
<li>In the January 1995 issue of The American Spectator ("Double-Crossing to Safety"), James Bovard 
reported on the FDA's raid on Proctor & Gamble's "Citrus Hill Fresh Choice" orange juice.  The FDA 
disputed the use of the word "fresh" on the label, saying it was misleading.  Proctor & Gamble noted a 
survey showing that consumers knew that "Fresh Choice" did not mean fresh squeezed, and besides, "Made 
from Concentrate" was also on the label.  Bovard reported: "Kessler ... took sweeping action: He ordered 
U.S. marshalls to seize the juice -- 12,000 gallons, as it turned out -- and destroy it.  Federal law declares 
that a 'misbranded' or 'mislabeled' product is automatically unsafe, and provides FDA with the authority to 
confiscate the merchandise."
<P>
Of course, the orange juice was both safe and healthy.  Dr. Kessler's actions, however, sent a signal that it 
was "get tough" time at the FDA, no matter how ridiculous the agency might seem.  Power would win out 
over reason.
<P>
<li>Bovard noted another raid.  This time the FDA launched an assault on vitamins not orange juice: "On 
May 6, 1992, a platoon of sixteen FDA inspectors and local police in flak jackets carried out a no-knock 
raid, smashing in the door of the Tahoma Clinic in Kent, Washington.  They held the staff at gunpoint, 
ostensibly so that nobody could try to hide the vitamins.  The raiders seized more than $100,000 in 
products and office supplies -- including address books and diaries -- and spent 14 hours cleaning out the 
office; they even tore the phones out of the wall.  FDA agents were supposedly concerned about the clinic's 
use of injected B-vitamins, which have been widely used in Germany with no adverse health problems."
<P>
<li>Commissioner Kessler was appointed by President George Bush, but reportedly lobbied hard to keep his 
job under President Clinton.  Kessler worked to ingratiate himself with the president-to-be with a list of 
aggressive regulatory actions.  On December 8, 1992, during the White House transition, Kessler offered 
his view of the FDA in remarks before the Food and Drug Law Institute's 36th Annual Educational 
Conference.  His emphasis on re-regulation and more aggressive enforcement was clear, as noted by the 
following excerpts:
<P>
"We needed to send out a message that, ultimately, it was in no one's interest to deregulate a public health 
regulatory agency."
<P>
"We're paying more attention to our field these days.  We've become once again an FDA that vigorously 
enforces the federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act, and not just an agency that approves products and 
educates consumers and the industry."
<P>
"Our enforcement people have fewer hoops to jump through, fewer boxes that must be checked off."
<P>
"We rely much less on voluntary agreements and much more on court-enforceable consent decrees."
<P>
"To complement the regular FDA field force we've created an Office of Criminal Investigations, not to be 
confused with the new Office of Investigations.  Thirty new special agents began intense training last week 
at a federal law enforcement training center in Georgia."
<P>
"In just over a year we've cleared the deck of uncompleted and abandoned regulatory proposals; we're 
getting new regulations out faster than ever before ..."
<P>
Commissioner Kessler, of course,  kept his job.
<P>
<li>This time writing in The Wall Street Journal (December 8, 1994), James Bovard observed another FDA 
tactic: "FDA employees are also sowing fear with a deluge of official Warning Letters (up more than 300% 
since Dr. Kessler took office).  Once the FDA issues a Warning Letter, it can seize a company's products or 
get a court injunction to paralyze its operations.  The FDA has refused to establish clear guidelines or rules 
for issuing its letters.  As a result, manufacturers can find themselves in a nightmare at the whim of a mid-
level FDA employee."
<P>
<li>In a letter to The American Spectator (April 1995), Dennis Plank, Editor-Publisher of the FDA Hotline, 
writes on how well federal regulatory agencies work together when it comes to regulatory crack downs: "A 
frightening current trend is how successful the FDA has become in pushing the buttons at other federal 
agencies to attack vitamin, supplement, and herbal manufacturers and suppliers.  We have reported on 
stepped-up enforcement actions by OSHA, FTC, Customs, Postal Service, and the DEA.  The Federal 
Trade Commission has now become the FDA's bully boy with no less than twenty cases pending against 
vitamin and natural product manufacturers."
<P>
<li>One of the FDA's most aggressive moves just occurred.  It did not involve a physical raid on a company's 
facilities.  Instead, it amounts to the beginnings of a power raid on an entire American industry.  According 
to published reports, on Wednesday, July 15, 1995, the FDA declared nicotine to be a drug, linking this 
conclusion to concern over tobacco products being sold to minors.  
<P>
Of course, it is currently illegal to sell tobacco products to minors.  In reality, the FDA's declaration of 
nicotine as a drug lays the ground work for extensive control over the manufacturing and distribution of 
tobacco products by the FDA.  
<P>
Most recognize that smoking is bad for your health, as are so many other undertakings.  Tobacco, like 
other things, is a legally grown, packaged, and sold product in the United States.  What happens now that 
the FDA is calling nicotine a drug?  Are tobacco farmers and convenience store owners to become outlaws, 
part of organized crime, or perhaps pharmacists?  Are the FDA's enforcement tactics, as described above, 
to be extended to tobacco farms and convenience stores?  What about smokers?  The effect of the FDA 
calling nicotine a drug goes well beyond concern over youth smoking -- it is an issue of extending the 
control of the nanny state.
<P>
Indeed, why stop at nicotine?  What about other habit forming substances?    For those of us who are 
overweight and enjoy drinking caffeine-laden beverages, will the FDA soon classify cheeseburgers, 
caffeine, and sugar as drugs -- how about hot dogs?
<P></ul>
As government agencies often do, the FDA has proven to be both hypocritical and incompetent.  Dr. 
Kessler and the FDA would better serve the public's health by improving the efficiency of their medical 
device and drug approval processes.  Unfortunately, Dr. Kessler's reign seems more about control.  It was 
reported in a recent article in Business Week (July 31, 1995) regarding Dr. Kessler, "Even close friends 
wonder if the bearded Long Island native might not do better to spend his time expediting approval for new 
drugs and medical devices, and fixing other FDA shortcomings."
<P>
The Washington Times reported on July 31, 1995 that former chief FDA investigator Jim Phillips sent a 
letter to the U.S. House Commerce panel on July 14 saying a half-dozen projects had been placed on hold 
due to the agency's obsession with investigating tobacco.  For example, Phillips is quoted as declaring the 
FDA's foreign inspection program as a "disaster waiting to happen."  He told the Times, "For the better part 
of the spring of 1994, Dr. Kessler spent virtually all of his time on cigarettes.  I can recall several instances 
in which I tried to contact Dr. Kessler on important matters and was told by his secretary that if my topic 
was anything other than cigarettes, the commissioner would have no time for me."
<P>
<hr>
<H3><a name="seven"><CENTER>FDA Budget  and Employees</a></CENTER></H3>
<P>
When confronted with such a checkered and costly performance record, many FDA defenders will say that 
the agency is simply in need of more resources.  However, FDA budget and employment levels tell quite a 
different story.
<P>
Figure 1, on the following page, shows the FDA's budget authority for select years since 1955 in inflation-
adjusted 1994 dollars.  Budget growth at the FDA indeed has been robust.  For example:
<P><ul>
<li>Just from 1989 to 1994, real FDA budget authority increased by 52.6 percent -- or by an average annual 
real rate of more than 10.5 percent.
<P>
<li>Between 1970 and 1994, real FDA budget authority increased by 221.1 percent.
<P>
<li>And between 1955 and 1994, the FDA's real budget authority rose by 2,978 percent.  Though the FDA's 
powers were enhanced considerably in the early 1960s, an average annual boost in real FDA budget dollars 
since 1955 of more than 76 percent is incredible.
<P>
 Figure 2 (page 16) illustrates the growth in employment at the FDA.  Again, a shortage of manpower does 
not seem to plague the agency.  For example:
<P>
<li>Between 1989 and 1994, FDA full-time employees grew by a substantial 25.3 percent.
<P>
<li>Between 1970 and 1994, FDA full-time employees increased by 115.7 percent.
<P>
<li>And between 1955 and 1994, full-time employees at the FDA increased by 933.4 percent.
<P></ul>
<hr>
<H3> <a name="eight"><CENTER>Incentives Problem</a></CENTER></H3>
<P>
Considering the great leaps in real budget authority and employment at the FDA, it would seem clear that 
the FDA does not lack for sufficient resources.  Instead, what the FDA lacks are proper incentives -- as is 
the case with most government undertakings.  Costs and performance in government -- unlike the private 
sector -- take a back seat to concerns over expanding power, budgets, and employment.  Without a profit 
motive, costs inevitably rise and performance declines.
<P>
In addition, the FDA possesses every incentive to prolong the drug and medical-device approval processes, 
since the agency monopolizes these activities and can face significant consequences when a problem 
develops in an approved product.  In contrast, the FDA loses virtually nothing when businesses and 
patients suffer because of agency delays.  Businesses and patients who die from FDA delays receive little 
attention.
<P>
In summary, taxpayers and consumers are spending more to get less from the FDA.  FDA delays, added 
costs, export restrictions, narrow-minded regulations, overly aggressive regulators, and mounting budgets 
are costing the United States in terms of lost businesses, jobs, and even lives.
<P>
Real reform means reduced costs and improved performance.  That translates into greater private-sector 
involvement in the safety of U.S. food, drugs, and medical devices.
<P>
<hr>
<H3><a name="nine"><CENTER>Market-Based Reforms</a></CENTER></H3>
<P>
The list of FDA shortcomings is quite lengthy.  Much to the chagrin of Commissioner Kessler, the FDA 
indeed should be "just an agency that approves products and educates consumers and the industry."  In the 
regulatory environment, anything more seems to breed hostility, often insurmountable costs, over-
zealousness, arrogance, big budgets, and massive intrusions on the part of regulators -- such as seizures of 
orange juice and armed raids on vitamin clinics.  
<P>
Entrepreneurs in the medical device, pharmaceutical, and food industries meet the most essential human 
needs -- sustenance and medical care.  The costs and risks of improving upon and/or creating new products 
in such areas remain substantial -- including the potential of enormous liability costs in a legal system gone 
awry.  Unfortunately, the FDA has managed to significantly add to these costs -- not only through delays 
and additional regulatory requirements, but through unpredictable, intrusive actions.    Entrepreneurs, 
however, are not the enemy; they are the driving force behind society's great leaps in technology, new 
products and services. 
<P>
The FDA's philosophy should not be one of making an example of a company in order to send a signal to 
other firms.  Instead, the agency should build a cooperative relationship with some of America's most 
dynamic and crucial industries.  Unfortunately, the FDA seems incapable of such a massive shift in attitude 
and culture.  Former U.S. Secretary of Health and Human Services Louis Sullivan was correct when he 
recently noted in The Washington Times (June 27, 1995) that the FDA may be beyond reform:
<P>
"Instead of making yet another effort to reform a system that seems incapable of reform, we should begin 
thinking about the design of a new system.  In my view, such a system would require considerable 
decentralization, perhaps along the lines of the European systems, where non-government institutions play 
a much greater role in the process of reviewing and approving new medical products."
<P>
One should be somewhat encouraged by the fact that the Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives also 
acknowledges considerable problems with the FDA.  In fact, Speaker Newt Gingrich went so far as to refer 
to the FDA as a "Stalinistic" agency and the "leading job killer" in the nation.  Under the FDA's yoke, 
entrepreneurs and businesses possess every incentive to cease research and development, shift operations 
and jobs out of the country, or close down altogether.
<P>
Bold steps need to be taken:  
<P><ul>
<li>The FDA should be scrapped in favor of a smaller agency geared toward safety and education.  
According to economist James Bovard, writing in the December 8, 1994 Wall Street Journal: "Rep. 
Gingrich favors replacing the FDA with an agency staffed with medical entrepreneurs, with strict limits on 
their time in government."  While one has to wonder why entrepreneurs would be willing to staff a 
government agency, the sentiment is correct.  
<P>
The Speaker's idea raises another question: Can FDA regulators ever be qualified enough to register sound 
judgments regarding  dynamic enterprises in, for example, the biomedical industry?  Tapping medical 
entrepreneurs is a good idea, but perhaps better achieved by allowing private firms to undertake safety 
approvals. 
<P>
The private sector -- medical entrepreneurs certified by the government -- is more capable of establishing 
an efficient drug and medical device approval processes.  Conceivably, the approval process would be 
contracted out, or preferably, companies themselves could hire private-sector entities for approvals.  
Universities, hospitals, researchers, and other firms could be certified by the government as drug or 
medical device approval entities.
<P>
<li>Efficacy should be left to the marketplace.  The government has a role in helping to secure consumers 
against substantial risks they could not know about -- i.e., safety -- as well as fraud.  Determining the 
efficacy of products, though, should be left to doctors, hospitals, experts, consumer groups, individuals, et 
al.
<P>
<li>Manufacturers and approval enterprises should be subject to the incentives of a sound legal system.  
However, huge awards for "pain and suffering" and punitive damages, contingency-fee lawyers, a plague 
of frivolous lawsuits, and much more, work against that soundness.  Product liability costs can terminate 
the life of a business, or simply extinguish it before an entrepreneur gives it life.  In such an environment, 
capital flees to industries where costs and risks are much smaller.
<P>
Industry often is regulated in one of two ways -- either by direct government regulation or through the 
legal system, i.e., the threat of a lawsuit.  Unfortunately, businesses must incur the costs of both systems 
today.  In the pharmaceuticals and medical device industries, the burdens of both government regulations 
and product liability are massive.
<P>
While firms should be liable for negligence or for misleading approval bodies, "regulatory compliance" 
and "state of knowledge" defenses should be allowed for firms that met all regulatory and safety 
requirements.
<P>
<li>The FDA currently disallows manufacturers from distributing information regarding off-label uses of 
drugs, such as independent studies and journal articles.  This dangerous ban should be lifted.  Doctors and 
patients need a steady flow of information about possible treatments.  Government, in no way, should 
hinder the free flow of information.
<P>
<li>A federal agency's enforcement powers, as well as its processes and standards for determining what 
products fall under its jurisdiction, should be scrutinized and reviewed annually by Congress.  Each 
individual policy decision approved by the President should receive the same examination.  Bizarre orange 
juice and vitamin raids should not be allowed to happen, nor should our elected officials be able to say that 
they were unable to stop such actions.
<P>
<li>The U.S. should negotiate and enter into agreements with other nations to recognize each other's drug 
and medical device approvals.
<P>
<li>Lastly, incentives for investment in dynamic industries, like pharmaceuticals and medical devices, need 
to be enhanced.  The aforementioned reforms are based on this premise.  Also, though having nothing to do 
with the FDA, one of the most productive steps that could be taken along this path is the elimination of 
capital gains taxes.  We have already noted the risky nature of drug and medical-device ventures.  High 
risks must be accompanied by at least the opportunity for substantial rewards.  A zero percent capital gains 
tax rate would help provide such opportunities -- boosting entrepreneurship, competition, and growth.
<P></ul>
The FDA is taking a heavy toll on the U.S. economy in terms of lost entrepreneurship, investment, jobs, 
and international competitiveness.  In a world where both capital and labor can move with increasing ease 
and freedom, the U.S. regulatory regime operates within an increasingly competitive global environment.  
A government agency that delays the approvals of beneficial drugs and medical devices to the degree that 
the FDA does, ensures that U.S.-based firms function at a severe disadvantage.  Of course, not only does 
this mean less investment, slower economic growth, and fewer jobs, but it also means that U.S. consumers 
often are denied access to life-saving  devices and treatments.
<P>
Competition can do wonders.  The U.S. regulatory regime acts as a severe drag on our economy.  Congress 
must act to make the U.S. food and drug regulatory environment more competitive on the world stage, or 
continue to lose cutting-edge firms and high-paying jobs to other nations.
<P>
<hr>
<H3><a name="ten"><CENTER>Still Tea Time at the FDA</a></CENTER></H3>
<P>
On February 23, 1993, The Wall Street Journal ran a story on its front page entitled "Perpetual Tea Time 
May Come to an End for Top U.S. Tea Taster," written by Bruce Ingersoll.  That's right, the federal 
government -- more specifically the FDA --employs tea tasters.
<P>
It seems that since the passage of the Tea Importation Act of 1897, federal taxpayers have paid for the U.S. 
Board of Tea Experts, with part of the board's tab picked up by the tea industry.  As a department of the 
FDA, the board's essential duty is to ensure that imported tea tastes alright.
<P>
Though certainly not a budget breaker, the FDA's tea tasters well represent the government's cavalier 
manner as to how it spends money.  The Journal reported that the Board of Tea Tasters costs about 
$200,000 annually, with its top tea taster making $60,000.  Upon entering office, President Clinton, like 
Presidents Nixon and Carter previously, was intent on terminating tea time at the FDA.
<P>
However, SBS Foundation called the FDA's Brooklyn, New York office -- home to the FDA's top tea taster 
-- in late July of this year.  The U.S. Board of Tea Experts still exists, answering the phone, "Tea room."  
<P>
Clearly, the FDA's tea room needs to go -- an example of government waste.  However, the Journal did 
report that many have praised Mr. Robert Dick -- the FDA's now 80-year-old tea taster -- as an 
"unbureaucratic bureaucrat."  A private-sector tea taster for Redco Foods Inc. reported, "In my experience, 
he evaluates tea the same day he receives it."  If lawmakers ever finally muster the courage to turn off the 
teapots at the FDA's tea room, maybe Mr. Dick could give some pointers to the FDA's drug and medical 
device departments on how to speed along approvals.
<P>
<br>
<center>
| <a href="/sbsc/i-sr.html">Special Reports Index</a> |</center>
