<center><a name="Proceed"></a><h3>PROCEEDINGS</h3></center>
<p><center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>

<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  (In progress) -- of the College
World Series, when the great events in this country.  I
happened to be here, as the Mayor knows, during the
College World Series.  <p>

		It's also the home of the "Entrepreneur of the
Year," Herman Cain of Godfather's Pizza.  And it is
under his auspices -- or at least aegis -- that we have
convened in Omaha.<p>

		And I would like the Commission to start with
some opening remarks from Mr. Cain, then the Mayor.  <p>

		And then we will proceed to our first panel.<p>

		Herman, thanks for your hospitality.  And we're
delighted to be in Omaha, Nebraska.<p>

<center><a name="Cain"></a>WELCOME BY COMMISSION MEMBER HERMAN CAIN</center>
<p><center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>

		<b>COMMISSIONER CAIN:</b>  Well, thank you, Jack.<p>

		I would simply like to say welcome to all of
the Commission Members who were able to make this
particular trip, because the schedule is somewhat tight
that our fearless leader has demanded in order for us
to get our job done.<p>

		And I am extremely proud of the fact that Omaha
was selected as one of the cities where we would have
one of our open hearings.<p>

		So, I simply would like to welcome all of the
Commissioners.  <p>

		I would like to welcome and thank everyone who
took time to attend today.<p>

		And I can tell you, from my own experiences in
attending the meetings thus far, that they have been
extremely interesting, extremely informative.  <p>

		And I am personally very optimistic about what
this Commission is today.  And today will be just
another step in being able to achieve, ultimately, what
our goal is.<p>

		So, as I indicated to someone earlier, when
they asked am I proud of the fact that we're having the
hearing here in Omaha, Nebraska, yes, I am -- very
proud.  <p>

		So, thank you, Jack. <p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Mayor Daub, thanks for joining
us and allowing us to be in your fair city.  It's a
pleasure to be with you.<p>

<center><a name="Daub"></a>OPENING REMARKS BY MAYOR HAL DAUB OF OMAHA, NEBRASKA</center>
<p><center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>

		<b>MAYOR DAUB:</b>  Well, Mr. Chairman -- and I used
to recall having the opportunity to say that to you
when you were my conference chairman when we served
together in the House of Representatives, it's always
good to see you and greet a friend and former
colleague.<p>

		And say to each of you a special and warm hello
from all of the citizens of Omaha, Nebraska, to
indicate to you that we feel honored.  <p>

		Not only are we proud of Herman Cain and all
that he does to help make this a sparkling and happy
and productive place to live, but you help us, as he
does, shine the spotlight on our city and our state of
Nebraska, and indeed the heartland.  <p>

		So, we bid you good morning and a welcome for
this second public hearing for the National Commission
on Economic Growth and Tax Reform.<p>

		This is the heartland.  We're very proud of our
productivity.  And you'll be listening to individuals,
men and women, on a very, very heavy schedule, as Mr.
Cain pointed out -- a very demanding schedule here in
Omaha today -- that speak for a variety and diversity
of business and industry.  They come from Illinois and
Iowa and Nebraska.  <p>

		So, I think you've well chosen this spot to
bring people together from the heartland and from the
greater Midwest to assess their view of where we need
to be in the years to come.<p>

		I'd like to extend a special welcome to all
those witnesses that you will have and to the people
who come to testify today.<p>

		And, of course, Jack, as I said, to especially
welcome you back so soon, when you were here to, I
guess, gauge how well this city can host and complement
opportunities as complex as the ones that you are
undertaking.<p>

		So, thank you, personally, each and every one
of you, for the work you're doing, for economic growth
and tax reform in our country.  		Through these
hearings and your report, people will be able to air
their concerns, ideas, and recommendations to help
stimulate economic growth in our country and to help
begin a process of tax reform. <p>

		I think, in fact, there are two great
happenings that are underway right now in our country.  <p>

		The first, from a Mayor's point of view, is a
Congress that is striving mightily to get their arms
around a gigantic federal system and to reshape it to
return power to local units of government and
particularly to do so without unfunded mandates.  I
think that's very significant, at least from the point
of view of governance. <p>

		The second, I think, great happening in America
is the undertaking of looking at our Tax Code -- and I
commend the Senator from Kansas, our Senator, Bob Dole
and the Speaker of the House, Newt Gingrich, for this
idea -- and, Jack, again, for your leadership in this
second great happening -- to see if we can't speak to
the future.<p>

		So, it is a historic opportunity.  		
Here, in Omaha city government, we're trying to set an
example for other communities and other units of taxing
authority to find innovative ways to approach tax
reform and economic growth.  <p>

		We've set priorities in our 1996 budget here so
we can begin to lower property tax rates for our
citizens.  We're engaged in that <p>

right-sizing process, too.  This will allow us to set a
pattern for meaningful tax reductions over the next few
years.  <p>

		We've also been hard at work to promote
economic growth in the 48th biggest city in America.  <p>

		Yes, Warren Buffet said he likes Omaha because
everything works in Omaha.  <p>

		And Walter Scott, of our Keywood Industries
organization, said he thought maybe the right answer to
Eddie was that maybe it's just the water.  <p>

		But whatever the reason, we're very proud of
what <i>Fortune</i> magazine said in rating Omaha "the ninth
most likely place you'd want to go if you want to set
your business on the fast track."  <p>

		In the high technology industry, to find one of
those cities, world-class cities of the 21st century,
you want to look at Omaha as high in brains and
entrepreneurial talent and the work ethic and work
productivity of this general area.  <p>

		So, we're mighty proud of how we're doing in
attracting more business and stimulating growth and
providing an atmosphere that will attract new
businesses and entrepreneurs that will help us grow.<p>

		I am confident you will seize this historic
opportunity and challenge all of us, but in particular,
as we take a look at this idea, that we can shed the
notion of our current tax policy and look to adopting a
more relevant process that will take us more fairly and
squarely to our future.<p>

		So, thanks again.  <p>

		Welcome to Omaha.  And I hope that you'll find
this hearing as informative as I know all of us will.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Thanks, Hal.<p>

		<b>MAYOR DAUB:</b>  Thank you very much.<p>

<center><a name="Kemp"></a>INTRODUCTION BY CHAIRMAN JACK KEMP</center>
<p><center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Thank you.<p>

		I introduced Herman Cain, who needs no
introduction.  <p>

		We're so pleased to have on our panel and our
Commission the president of the American Farm Bureau,
Dean Kleckner -- and as the Mayor said, we're in the
heartland of America -- thank you, Hal -- in the
heartland of America, no more important issue than tax
reform, entrepreneurship, working, saving, investing,
building a business, building a farm, investing in your
family.  These are the issues that our Commission is
undertaking.  <p>

		We are particularly pleased, on this
Commission, to have Loretta Adams, an entrepreneur --
and impresario from San Diego, California; Jack Faris,
the president of the National Federation of Independent
Business, NFIB, one of America's -- if not America's
premier representative of small, independent working
entrepreneurs and men and women in this country.<p>

		John Wieland, a homebuilder, one of the
distinguished homebuilders from Atlanta, Georgia.	<p>

		Teddy Forstmann, the founder of Forstmann
Little and one of American's financiers.<p>

		Shirley Peterson, former Commissioner of the
IRS, whose recent article was so perceptive in
outlining the problems of the current Code and some of
the answers that we are seeking.<p>

		Matt Fong, on my right, is the Treasurer of the
State of California, one of the rising stars not only
on the political scene but among the state treasurers
of the country.<p>

		Ken Blackwell, State Treasurer of Ohio is not
here, nor is John Snow, the CEO of CSX, who is in
Europe.  But they'll be joining us.<p>

		This is our sixth opening meeting.  This is our
second field hearing.  We were in Boston, now Omaha. 
We're going to Charlotte and San Francisco.  <p>

		We're also going to hold some tangential
hearings in different inner cities of the country to
explore the nexus between tax policy and poverty and
the problems of <p>

low-income minority entrepreneurs.<p>

		So, we're going to the run the gamut.  We have
heard from Democrats and Republicans.  Last night we
heard from Warren Buffet.  <p>

		Today we've got three panels.  We're going to
try to keep them within the range of <p>

45 minutes, have a break of about 10 to 15 minutes at
around 10:30, close down around <p>

12 o'clock, maybe 12:15.<p>

		We're going to have a little press availability
and then some Godfather's Pizza thanks to Herman Cain.<p>

		(Applause)<p>

		Thank you fellow employees of Godfather's
Pizza.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		One of the nice things about being chairman is
that everybody is sending me books.  I just sit back in
my office and look at books and articles and papers.  <p>

		And, you know, it really is interesting,
because somehow taxes -- it isn't <p>

-- somehow, it is absolutely a fact, taxes touch every
aspect of our lives.  It alters behavior.  It modifies
people's acts.  <p>

		The most recent book sent to me was "Good and
Evil, the Impact of Taxes in the History of
Civilization."  <p>

		Now, that's quite a study, but it goes back to
the Genesis -- the Book of Genesis and Abraham's -- I'm
sorry, Joseph's advice to Pharaoh.		<p>

		One of my favorite quotes was sent to me the
other day from my youngest son, who majored in
economics at Wake Forest.  <p>

		And he said, "Dad, I think you guys are on to
something."  <p>

		That's a tremendous concession from my son,
Jimmy Kemp.  But he's 23 years old and playing football
and he wrote.  He sent me a little Xeroxed page from
Will and Ariel Durant's "Story of Civilization" and
"The Decline of Greece," democracy in the Greek period,
and it said -- and I quote:<p>

		"The assembly degenerated into a mob, rejected
all restraint, voted itself every favor, and taxed the
people to the point of crushing their initiative, their
industriousness, and their thrift.  And democracy never
rose again."<p>

		The question was asked this morning of me by
one of the press representatives, "Are you a
Republican?"<p>

		I said, in answering, "We're center right. 
We're democratic Republicans."<p>

		There has to be a party -- there has to be a
movement in this country devoted to making democracy
work for all people.  <p>

		And the purpose of our hearings is to hear men
and women who are interested in <p>

tabula rasa vis-a-vis the Tax Court and writing a new
one, as Bob Dole and Newt Gingrich charged us with, for
the 21st century.  	<p>

		We're not going to wait for the 21st century,
because we want to present our product by the end of
October, maybe the end of November, and allow Democrats
and Republicans to look at the product of this
Commission's hearings and deliberations and to be in
Omaha with you, Herman, and you, Dean, our fellow
Commissioners in the first panel, to carry out what Bob
Dole and Newt Gingrich said was to bring about a
flatter, fairer, simpler, lower, pro-growth Tax Code
for American entering the 21st century.  <p>

		So, we see ourselves in a sense as the Founding
Fathers.  Maybe if a constitutional convention -- not
to suggest that any one of us have the incredible
intellect of those incredible people.  But we want to
look at the Code with an eye on how this country can
work better in a post-Cold War era of tremendous
possibilities, tremendous and exciting possibilities.<p>

		Let me suggest that our -- invite the first
panel, who will make a presentation of a perspective
from business and industry.<p>

		I'm going to ask Frank Hayes, the president of
Hayes &amp; Associates; Leroy Thom, president of T&amp;L
Irrigation Company; J. William Henry, executive vice
president, First National Bank of Omaha; Richard
Abramson, president and CEO of Prairie Systems, Inc.;
Gerald Schenken -- Dr. Schenken is president of The
Pathology Center; and Jeff Renner, principal office of
the Freeman Company.<p>

		If anybody in the audience who would like to
present a question to the panel, we are going to take
questions, but we're going to take them written down. 
That isn't to inhibit anybody; it is simply to try to
provide a little order to what could be a chaotic
process.  <p>

		We want to hear people -- very important that
this Commission hear from citizen groups.  <p>

		Talmudic philosopher said, one time, "There's a
lot of wisdom in the world.  Unfortunately, it's all
divided up among the people."<p>

		We don't think that's unfortunate.  We think
that's the best way; that's how markets work.  We think
markets are efficient, and we're delighted, gentlemen,
that you would be here.<p>

		And I'm going to start with Frank Hayes,
president of Hayes &amp; Associates, and move down.  We
would appreciate your brevity, but nonetheless we want
to hear the synthesis of your approach to tax policy. <p>

		Mr. Hayes, thank you for being here.<p>

<a name="Hayes"></a><center>PRESENTATION BY FRANK HAYES<br>
PRESIDENT, HAYES &amp; ASSOCIATES</center>
<p>
<center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>

		<b>MR. HAYES:</b>  Thank you.<p>

		First of all, I'd like to thank everyone.	<p>

		I just want to thank the Commission for
inviting me to come and give my perspective. <p>

		When I -- when Herman -- I know Herman -- when
-- I call him Herman -- hopefully, he doesn't get upset
about that.  <p>

		But when Herman first talked to me about this,
I hadn't really thought about tax reform.  And he was
telling me that he was involved on the Commission and
wanted to know what my perspectives were.  And we
talked a little bit.<p>

		He said, "I think you'd be a good person to
come and talk before the Commission."<p>

		Just to give you a little bit of background,
just to give you some sense about where I'm coming
from, I'm a CPA by profession.  I am a former IRS
agent.  At one time I also worked with an international
accounting firm for a number of years as the head of
their tax department.<p>

		(Off-mike remarks)<p>

		<b>MR. HAYES:</b>  Oh, yeah, let me switch gears.<p>

		There goes the brevity. <p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  We'll decide that, Frank.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		<b>MR. HAYES:</b>  As I said, I was an IRS agent.  I
worked for an international accounting firm for several
years.  <p>

		And also, after that, I started my own
accounting firm in 1983, so I've been in business as
Hayes &amp; Associates for the last 12 years.<p>

		And in doing this, we've worked with some
businesses, individuals, corporations, <p>

not-for-profit organizations.  And all of those
particular clients are all concerned about taxes.  And
we spent an enormous amount of time over those number
of years trying to figure out how to cut taxes for
people.  <p>

		And I think my basic thrust on this whole issue
is that I think if there's a way to make things more
simple, more fair, and sort of take the tax aspect out
of making day-to-day business decisions, I think
everybody would become productive.<p>

		As an accountant -- and as you know, we do a
lot of a tax work -- so a lot of people would say,
"Sell, as an accountant, how can you advocate making
something simpler, when it might make you lose your
job?"<p>

		Well, I think, as advisers, as business
advisers, as CPAs, we can still be more -- we can be
more productive if we can divorce ourselves from having
to make decisions strictly on a tax basis.	<p>

		And as you said, Chairman Kemp, it touches
everything that we do.  And if there is a way for us to
change that, so that as we go day to day in our
individual life or in our business life, where we can
make business decisions and not tax decisions, I think
it makes everyone more productive.<p>

		I don't know exactly all the specifics of what
you've talked about as far as how you're going forward
with this.  Maybe you haven't formulated those yet.  <p>

		But one of the things that I think happens with
a business -- and we work with a lot of businesses --
people come into the office and they say, "Well, how
can I cut my taxes?  How can I cut my taxes?"  <p>

		And that's more -- the biggest decision that we
have to sit down and talk to them about.  And a lot of
people get very frustrated, because we have business
owners who invest in their business, they go out and
they buy new equipment, they renovate or rehab their
facilities.  And then, at the end of the year, they
say, "Well, can't I deduct that?"  <p>

		And we say, "No.  You have to capitalize it and
depreciate it."<p>

		So, the person -- and then you've got to pay
taxes on money you reinvested back in the business.<p>

		So, people say, "Well, I don't have any money. 
The money isn't there.  I put it all back in the
business.  How am I going to pay these taxes?"<p>

		So, I guess, in my way of thinking, I think if
there is a way, as a Commission, that you can formulate
some ideas that will allow business decisions to be
made more on an economic basis, as opposed to a tax
basis, I think you would go real, real far in making
things a lot more simple, and also creating more
productivity in the meantime.<p>

		And as an accountant, I feel like it would be
an opportunity for us, as advisers, to do a better job
of advising our business clients, instead of just
focusing on the tax orientation.<p>

		The other thing I'd like to say is, is that
there are some, I guess, adverse things I think I need
to say about tax reform.  And as I said, I think one of
them is that, as a CPA, it's obviously going to impact
our business.  So, no one in their right mind would
advocate doing something that's going to do away with
the revenue source for them. <p>

		The other thing I might say is that I'm
concerned a little bit about it -- and I would hope
that you guys consider this in your deliberations.  I'm
concerned about charitable organizations.  I feel very
strongly that charitable organizations do a great
service in this country.  <p>

		And to a large degree, at least in my
experience, some people make charitable donations
because they feel they can deduct them for tax
purposes.  Now, maybe that's not the main reason, but
in a lot of cases that's one of the reasons.  So, I
think there should be some consideration given to that.<p>

		Another thing that I think that has happened
with the Tax Code over the last several years -- and I
know, Chairman Kemp, you're very in favor of this -- is
enterprise zones.  And there are some tax incentives
that go with that.  		And I think whatever you do
there should be some kind of consideration given to
encourage, incent (sic), whatever you will, economic
development in depressed areas.  And the enterprise
zones have been a good way to do that, and you've used
the Tax Code to try to get that done.<p>

		So, I think if you do make it simpler, you
still should have those kinds of things incorporated in
your plan so that there is some incentive to invest in
economically depressed areas.<p>

		But in summary, I guess I would say that I'm
very much in favor of some kind of simplification
process.  I sort of come there.  I wasn't there.  I
wasn't there when I first heard about this, because of
the things I said earlier.  <p>

		But I think what it would allow us to do as
advisers -- and, also, would allow the business to do -- is make better decisions, better business decisions,
and get so much away from the tax implications and more
on the economic side.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Well said.  Thank you, Frank,
very much.     <p>

		Leroy.<p>

<a name="Thom"></a><center>PRESENTATION BY LEROY THOM</center>
<p><center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>

<center>PRESIDENT, T&amp;L IRRIGATION CO.</center>
<p>

		MR. <b>MR. THOM:</b>  Thanks to the Commission to having
me here.<p>

		I'm a small businessman, celebrating my
fortieth anniversary.  Our company is T&amp;L Irrigation,
Hastings, Nebraska.  We sell irrigation equipment in
all of the states and in 12 foreign countries.  And at
the present time, we have 200 employees. <p>

		We all know that taxes are too high.  And we
have structured taxes so they slow economic growth.  <p>

		And I'm going to give you some of my personal
experience.  <p>

		Tax forms need to be simplified.  In 1994, our
tax form was the size of a small textbook.  We put
approximately 500 hours of our own, in-house, preparing
it.  The CPA put 230 hours preparing it.  And I don't
think -- only one knew somewhat what we were doing, and
that was the CPA.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		I had to sign that, but I didn't know exactly
what I was signing, except -- you know.  		So, what
has happened is Congress has made the tax laws and
regulations so complex that it takes someone who
specializes in tax law, working full-time, to interpret
these laws and regulations.<p>

		We have to find some way to get it down,
simple.<p>

		The last time I was audited by the IRS, it took
13 months to get the audit over.  At the end of 13
months, they didn't find enough mistakes to pay for
their people that were at the office.  Plus, I don't
know how many hours my staff put in helping them with
the audit.<p>

		A lot of time -- and pretty much what Frank
says, a lot of time is spent by everyone to minimize
their taxes because of the current laws.  This time
would be better spent in making profit for the
business.<p>

		There are many changes needed to be made in the
tax law, but here are a couple of what I call someone
asinine things. <p>

		Depreciation laws need to be reformed so a
taxpayer can advantage of the deduction in his
lifetime.<p>

		For example, I am building a new office.  It
will be depreciated for 39-1/2 years.  I'll be 110 if
I'm lucky.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		My youngest son will be 75.<p>

		Now, that is one thing.  Another one is we have
a lot of people on the road.  We have truck drivers,
servicemen, and salesmen.  We only get to deduct 50
percent of their meals.  Isn't this a legitimate
expense of business?<p>

		Another one is laws requiring retirement plans
need to made simpler.  We need to encourage taxpayers
to save for their retirement.  The current laws are so
complex and the fees and the administration costs of
these retirement plans are so prohibitive that many
small businesses can't offer this program to their
employees.  <p>

		Now, we come to taxes.  At the present time,
the federal and state tax puts T&amp;L at 46 percent.  This
does not include real estate tax, property tax,
personal tax, sales tax, fuel tax, and so forth.  <p>

		Then we come to the most regressive tax, estate
tax.  T&amp;L already has paid 46 cents.  When I pass on,
my estate will pay 55 percent of the last 54, which is
30 cents, which means that it can total 76 cents of
every dollar that I pay (sic) goes to those two taxes,
which does not include that other list of taxes that I
had.	<p>

		Worst of all, this means that the family
business will need to be sold in many cases to pay the
estate taxes.  <p>

		In my case, I have two sons in the business,
and I'd like to keep the business in the family.  But
with the current estate tax, this may not be possible.  <p>

		This will be detrimental not only to my family,
but also long-term employees.  This is very true in the
family farm in our area.  <p>

		You know, a family farm in our area is from 640
acres to 4,000 acres of row crop.  Many times, so much
of this ground has to be sold to pay the estate tax,
that when the next generation takes control, the family
farm is too small to be profitable, and they lose the
whole thing.<p>

		So, in summary:<p>

			Simplification of taxes and forms.<p>

			Improved incentives of capital expenditure
to create more business.<p>

			Reduce the estate tax to help preserve
small business and family farms.<p>

			Reduce the maximum tax rate to encourage
expansion and economic growth.<p>

			Get the government off the business backs,
such as OSHA, EPA, and all the other regulations that
are needed.		<p>

		In closing, this is a little bit off the
subject, the problem is the government is spending too
much.  I feel the only way that you can reduce
government spending is across-the-board spending cuts
so all divisions of government are taking a cut.  <p>

		Government is unwanted partner in business.  It
only takes the cream, doesn't help the business, takes
all of the profits out, and feeds nothing back to make
it grow.		<p>

		Thank you much for the opportunity.<p>

		(Applause)<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Well, Leroy, you have spoken on
behalf of all of the Commissioners.  And I'm sure with
all due respect to our panelists, I just can't help but
mention, on behalf of the Commission, that you are
preaching to the choir.  This is why Bob Dole and
Newt Gingrich set up this Commission.  <p>

		And hang in there, Leroy.  Help is on the way.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		You speak for every small businessman and woman
in America.  We appreciate your testimony.<p>

		MR. <b>MR. THOM:</b>  Thank you.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Bill, executive vice president
for First National Bank of Omaha.<p>

		Bill, thank you -- or William, whichever you
would like to be called.<center></center>
<p>

<a name="Henry"></a><center>PRESENTATION BY J. WILLIAM HENRY<br>
EXECUTIVE VICE PRESIDENTFIRST NATIONAL BANK OF OMAHA </center>
<p>
<center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>

		<b>Mr. HENRY:</b>  I thank the Commission for the
opportunity to testify in this important matter.<p>

		The First National Bank and its affiliates
operate community banks in four Midwestern states, with
total assets of approximately $6 billion, and we employ
just over 4,000 people.  We are a leader in
agricultural lending and equipment leasing.  <p>

		We are committed to Main Street, retail and
small business lending in our communities, and we are
one of the Nation's leading issuers of bank card and
processing merchant transactions.<p>

		Our effective tax rate is one of the highest in
the country for financial institutions.  It has, on
average, exceeded the statutory tax rate over the last
three years.  As of June 30, 1995, our effective
federal tax rate is 35.102 percent.  <p>

		We are not a company which seeks to avoid our
taxes.  We're a good corporate citizen, and we support
a simpler tax system in which everyone will pay their
fair share.  It is good for our country, our customers
as well as ourselves.<p>

		We believe in real, meaningful tax reform.  The
cost in financial management resources of complying
with the current federal Tax Code places a tremendous
burden on all business and weighs most heavily on the
smallest and most entrepreneurial businesses.  <p>

		The costs of taxes are, in and of themselves, a
highly regressive tax, taking a proportionately much
higher toll on small business than on large business. 
This is a problem.<p>

		Furthermore, the current Tax Code is filled
with exceptions, exemptions, alternatives, and offsets,
which tend to benefit bigger business, better equipped
to take full advantage of all potential tax benefits. 
This is also a problem.<p>

		From a banker's perspective, a simpler, more
cost-effective, and fairer Tax Code is going to help
our economy.  It will free capital and management
resources to invest in the future and produce more
jobs.  <p>

		It will also increase the demand for bank
credit, to help fund this investment.  This will
benefit banks; and through the laws of supply and
demand, it will benefit our depositors as well.<p>

		Tax reform really can be good for everyone, but
we encourage you to carefully consider two issues which
could undermine the very advantages you hope to create
through tax reform.<p>

		First, be careful how you tax financial
institutions.  There seems to be a perception among
lawmakers that banks are somehow special and difficult
to tax.  This is really not true.  Banks are
fundamentally like all businesses.  <p>

		We have raw material costs, manufacturing
costs, inventory costs, and gross margins.  Our only
real difference is that our raw material and our
finished product are dollars, as opposed to tons or
units.  <p>

		So, tax proposals which exempt investment
income from taxation have a problem with banks, since
they confuse our finished product with investment.<p>

		Bank deposits and bank interest income must be
treated as the raw material costs and rent receipts
that they are.  This is the only way to permit the
market to define bank income on an institution-by-institution basis.  <p>

		We strongly urge you not to succumb to the
temptation of using an arbitrary formula or simplistic
and inaccurate assumptions about market cost to mask
the issue.<p>

		Second, be aware of a growing national problem
being created by state taxation of interstate commerce
in intangible goods and services.  <p>

		This is not a federal tax issue.  This is a
federal issue.  The taxation of interstate commerce --
and it is the potential to severely undermine the
benefits of all federal tax reform.  <p>

		The core of the problem is that every state can
and should tailor its tax codes to its own unique
needs.  This exposes companies involved in interstate
commerce to double and triple taxation.<p>

		As more states become aware of their right
companies located in other states, they have begun to
seek back taxes and alter their codes to increase the
proportion of state tax which can be collected out-of-state.  <p>

		The costs of implementation, compliance, and
litigation are continuing to mount.  The effect on the
national economy of these costs and the immeasurable
cost of uncertainty about the future should not be
understated.  <p>

		This is not just a bank issue.  It involves
technology, communications, and services generally, and
it will affect our global competitiveness.<p>

		The 86th Congress recognized this basic problem
and forbid states to tax companies which have no
presence within their borders except sales
relationships.  <p>

		But in 1959, when the U.S. had a goods economy,
the protection provided was specifically limited to
tangible goods.  We now have a service economy, and the
interstate commerce in services and intangibles is not
covered by federal protection.  <p>

		The solution to this problem is simple,
congressional action to extend existing service to
services and intangibles, but the solution is
politically difficult for the federal government and
potentially expensive for state governments.<p>

		Unfortunately, the longer we wait to resolve
it, the more expensive and difficult it will become. 
We strongly urge the Commission to address this serious
problem in your report.<p>

		Thank you for letting me testify.  A copy of my
remarks are available for you.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Thank you.  Thank you, Mr.
Henry.<p>

		Mr. Abramson.<p>

<a name="Abramson"></a><center>PRESENTATION BY J. RICHARD  ABRAMSON.<br>
PRESIDENT AND CEO, PRAIRIE SYSTEMS, INC.</center>
<p>
<center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>




		<b>MR. ABRAMSON:</b>  Well, thank you, Mr. Chairman. 
I really appreciate the opportunity here to come and
speak before the Commission and at the invitation of
the NFIB.<p>

		I am a small businessman here in Omaha, the
founder of a company by the name of Prairie Systems
that develops software for the high technology
industry, primarily telecommunications.  We're a five-year-old company and growing very rapidly very
recently.  We were given an award as "The Second-
Fastest Growing Company in Omaha."	<p>

		The Tax Code has a great impact on our business
and our need for capital.  <p>

		I also was the chairman of the White House
Conference on Small Business for the Nebraska
delegation that recently met.  And I can tell you that
taxation was one of the hottest topics at the White
House Conference on Small Business.<p>

		I would also tell you that Mr. Thom -- his
testimony very much reflects that of the small business
community that was represented there.  And I second
everything that he said.<p>

		The thing I believe that is encouraging here is
that there are a number of proposals out for tax
reform, and I really commend you for that.<p>

		The high, progressive tax system today
discourages savings and investment.  And that's the
aspect that I want to hit on today, because I've felt
the pinch of this.  And certainly that discouragement
of savings and investment seriously harms the economy
by reducing capital formation and investment in small
business such as mine.  <p>

		In my opinion, an ideal tax system does not
penalize or subsidize various economic choices. 
However, I think the current tax system does, in fact,
do that.<p>

		Unfortunately, one of the most destructive
elements of the current Tax Code is the multiple levels
of taxation on investment and savings.  <p>

		Just as savings, dividends, businesses and
other forms of investment income are penalized by
personal income tax, capital  formation is hindered by
corporate income tax, capital gains taxes, estate and
gift taxes, depreciation tax, and by corporative
alternative minimum taxes. <p>

		An example here is if a taxpayer, after he pays
his personal income tax, has $100 to do something with. 
One choice he can do is go out and consume that, spend
it on goods and services or vacations and haircuts, and
various things like that, and, with the exception of
sales tax, get about $100 worth of benefit from that
$100.<p>

		Alternatively, he can make a choice to invest
those dollars in a small business like mine or many
others that fuel the growth in this country.  In that
case, he takes the opportunity to create new jobs and
to spur the economy and create new products and
services.<p>

		If the company succeeds, the investor will
likely benefit from that.  Alternatively, he's put it
completely at risk, and that $100 may disappear.<p>

		In the example here, let's assume that this
investment does bear fruit and gets a 10 percent return
on that, which means that the investment yields $10 of
income for every $100 invested.  <p>

		Under the current Tax Code, 34 percent of that
is skimmed to pay the corporate income tax, leaving
only $6.60 out of that original $10.  <p>

		Let's assume that $6.60 then goes to the
investor as a dividend, but he then faces other taxes. 
Depending on the investor's income, the personal income
tax will take as much as 40 percent off of his $6.60,
leaving him less than $4 of annual income in this
successful investment that he made.  In addition, he
probably has some form of state and local taxes to pay.<p>

		Finally, if this investor decides to sell off
this stock, he now gets subjected to -- hit by one of
the highest capital gains taxes in the industrialized
world.  <p>

		And I think the White House Conference on Small
Business gave very large support to reduction or
elimination of the capital gains tax.<p>

		What little income he eventually receives from
saving and investment have taken <p>

-- it's a small return compare to the risk that he has
had to take to get it there.<p>

		To add insult to injury, as Mr. Thom has
pointed out, successful entrepreneurs who are trying to
accumulate an estate, then, to pass on to their
children face the possibility of 55 percent taxation on
those assets.<p>

		Thanks to the Tax Code, a fortunate investor,
one who actually earns money on his investment, may
have to send more than half of his earnings to the
government, not to mention having already paid taxes on
the money in the first place that he invested.<p>

		In my opinion, by punishing this savings and
investment, this Tax Code encourages businesses and
individuals to consume rather than save and to build
America.  <p>

		As a result, to small business owners like
myself, there is very limited capital available.  We're
a very high-growth business, and it takes a lot of
capital to grow at that rate.  <p>

		The results of investment, venture capital
kinds of firms demand a 50 percent annual return and up
on their investments in order to, first of all,
mitigate some of the risks that they've taken, but also
to return a decent profit to their organization after
all these taxes have been paid.<p>

		My business is ideal to that sort of venture
investment, and it's enormously expensive to build and
grow a small business with that.<p>

		I believe that a consumption-based tax, with
careful attention to the avoidance of this double
taxation, should be the goal of tax reform.<p>

		I think there's a real danger here, though, in
that the mechanism for getting from where we are to any
form of tax, but especially a consumption tax, I think
is especially ticklish.  And the worst of all worlds
would be to end up with both an income tax and some
form of an income (sic) tax.<p>

		And so in my opinion, a shift to a consumption
tax would require repeal of the 16th Amendment to get
rid of income tax.  <p>

		I do applaud the efforts of this Commission.  <p>

		The small business community is enormously
concerned about these issues.  It's long overdue that
we have tax reform in this country.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Thank you very much.<p>

		And now we turn to Dr. Schenken.<p>

<p>

<a name="Schenken"></a><center>PRESENTATION BY JERALD SCHENKEN, M.D.<br>
PRESIDENT, THE PATHOLOGY CENTER</center>
<p>
<center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>




		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  Thank you very much, <p>

Mr. Chairman.  <p>

		And because of time constraints, I have
submitted some written testimony -- <p>

		CHAIRMAN MILES:  Sure.<p>

		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>: -- which I hope you'd put in the
record for me.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Well, please be assured that
the written testimony will be passed along to all of
the members of the Commission, and it will be part of
our official record -- and also the Commissioners who
aren't here.  So, we appreciate that. <p>

		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  Thank you very much.<p>

		It's a pleasure to be here.  <p>

		I'm president of a medical laboratory.  We have
about 210 employees.  We provide laboratory services
for doctors, patients, and hospital in western Iowa,
northwestern Missouri, and Nebraska.<p>

		As you may or may not know -- those of you are
involved in health care may know that while there are
probably some competitive problems out there in health,
that doesn't run over into the lab area, which has been
competitive for about 25 years.  <p>

		And we compete every day with multibillion
dollar organizations.  And I can tell you competition
is fun, but it's hard work.<p>

		About 50 percent of our employees are
professionally trained.  The majority of them are
female.  About 70 percent of our employees are from
two-income families.  And a significant number of our
senior managers are female and are the senior earners
in their families.<p>

		I bring this to you because I want you to know
the perspective from which I am going to raise some
issues.<p>

		Now, I have also been a former board member of
both the Nebraska and the Omaha Chamber of Commerce and
long-time member of the NFIB.  And twice I was elected
to the White House Conference on Small Business.  <p>

		And I have had the privilege of testifying
hundreds of times on issues relating to health or
economics or tax issues in front of Congress.<p>

		So, let me open my testimony by telling you
what I experienced.<p>

		1984, I believe, was the 10-year anniversary of
ERISA.  And there was a Labor Department hearing on the
thing.  <p>

		And I testified, and I said, "You know, health
was included in ERISA by accident," which I believe it
to have been. <p>

		And what happened was that because of ERISA's
exemption, we had one aspect of the health insurance of
the United States which was completely free of state
regulation, state mandate, state this, state that, and
left the insurance companies noncompetitive because
they all had all of the mandates, they had all of the
regulations, and so forth.<p>

		I'm not saying one is good or one is bad, but
this is just one of many examples in which the
discrepancies within these regulatory and tax --
ultimately tax codes did not jive and left small
businesses -- I'll tell you in a minute -- holding the
bag.<p>

		Now, basically I believe the problem to be that
there are huge numbers of incentives and disincentives
in the current tax law and code.  And as a doctor, I
could call them disordered, dysfunctional, and
destructive.<p>

		And my big call to you, as you simplify them,
make sure they go in the same direction and they help
businesspeople make business decisions to be productive
and create wealth and so forth, rather than going in
the other directions.<p>

		And I'm going to focus quickly on four issues
that relate to small businesses, my operation and
others:		<p>
<ul>
<li>Health insurance,
<li>The marriage penalty.
<li>Inheritance tax.
<li>And spending.
</ul><p>
		Health insurance -- small business has been
chided for not providing health insurance by people who
don't understand small business.  There are two real
reasons for it.  <p>

		One is we have not been able to create the type
of groups we need to.  That's another issue.<p>

		But the other has been that individuals and
small businesses have been prevented from having the
tax sheltering ability that normal corporations have.  	<p>

		I provide my employees through -- I'm a
professional corporation, and we provide them -- for
everybody.  But my small business colleagues, my farmer
friends, and so forth are penalized by the Tax Code,
and then they're penalized again because they have to
get individual tax policies.<p>

		And while I'm on health, I think we should
recognize one of your panel members, who is one of two
people -- I won't mention the other one -- but one of
the two people who stood up at the time when health was
about to be nationalized and said, "Small business
can't deal with this."<p>

		Thank you, Mr. Cain.<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  Here, here.<p>

		(Applause)<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  -- all by himself.  A lot of
help, but -- that was the beginning, in my opinion --<p>

		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  He had one --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  In my opinion -- editorial
comment here -- that was the beginning of the end to
the --<p>

		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  That was it.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  -- nationalized health
