<a name="Renner"></a><center>PRESENTATION BY JEFF RENNER<br>
PRINCIPAL OFFICER, THE FREEMAN CO., INC.</center>
<p>
<center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>


		MR. RENNER:  Thank you, Chairman Kemp and
members of the Commission.<p>

		I'm a small businessman, also, primarily
engaged in banking and real estate.  However, I've also
had 15 years of experience in government.<p>

		You've heard an awful lot of reasons today why
there should be a major overhaul of the Nation's Tax
Code.  <p>

		But the single over-riding reason is this, that
the current Tax Code is an enormous waste of
everybody's time.<p>

		A Heritage Foundation study estimated that
Americans spend 5.4 billion manhours annually complying
with the Tax Code and with tax planning and record-keeping and tax return preparation.<p>

		And I saw a recent article in the Wall Street
Journal that estimated that the current Tax Code costs
our economy 6 billion hours annually.<p>

		So, I did some quick calculations.  That's the
equivalent of 10,000 lifetimes wasted every year.<p>

		According to the Tax Foundation, the compliance
costs for the federal income tax last year cost
American business alone $127 billion.  And it cost all
Americans $200 billion.  That's an amount equal to the
output of our automobile, truck, and aircraft
industries combined. <p>

		That time and effort and money did not educate
a single child, it didn't feed a single family, and it
didn't produce a single tangible product to improve the
life of anyone.<p>

		The main reason for this waste of time and
money is the sheer complexity of the Tax Code.  In its
present form, it's impossible for many Americans to
even comply with the tax laws simply because they can't
understand it.<p>

		I had the personal experience at one time of
being told by the government to handle a transaction in
a certain manner, only to be audited and later told
that it should have been done differently.  <p>

		Unfortunately, ignorance of the law is no
excuse for we American citizens.  But equally as
unfortunate, the ignorance of the law seems to be the
only excuse required of our employees.<p>

		Another focus of the Commission's work is the
basic principles and objectives that the reform plan
must embody.  And I would suggest that these are three: 
Simplicity, stability, and fairness.<p>

		A recent Andersen Consulting survey revealed
that simpler forms and filing instructions were among
individuals' top tax concerns.  And I saw another
survey that showed that over 70 percent of the college
graduates in this country can't compute their own
taxes.<p>

		Now, our Tax Code should be simple enough so
that an individual is able to prepare and file his or
her own tax return.<p>

		I'm one of those college graduates who can't
file his own tax return.  And last year it cost me over
$5,000 just to file my own personal tax return.  And
that's ridiculous.<p>

		The current complexity of the Tax Code leads, I
think, to this instability.  In an eight-year period,
we've seen six major tax bills pass the Congress.  <p>

		And these constant attempts to correct or fine
tune the Tax Code lead to more change and more
uncertainty, making it impossible for individual
Americans to meaningfully plan for their own future.<p>

		Americans need to be able to understand what
the Tax Code is and know that it's going to remain
reasonably stable.<p>

		Finally, the Tax Code must be fair, and this is
the most difficult term to define.  But we do know that
the current Tax Code pits organized special interest
groups with money and lobbyists against families with
children and limited resources.  They can't compete in
that arena.<p>

		The current tax compliance system costs small
businesses proportionately 10 times more than large
corporations, as Mr. Henry pointed out.<p>

		A fair Tax Code, I suppose, would be one that's
more uniform, that would tax all income without special
exceptions and loopholes, hopefully at a lower rate;
that it would tax all income the same way, regardless
of the source, and would tax it only once. <p>

		By eliminating the complexity and introducing
stability and fairness through uniformity, I think that
we, as a nation, can redirect our time and energy and
resources toward production and economic growth.<p>

		Thank you.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Great.  Thank you.<p>

		Thank all of you.  Very eloquent.<p>

		Herman Cain -- Mr. Cain.<p>

		<b>COMMISSIONER CAIN:</b>  Thank you, Chairman Kemp. <p>

		I want to direct my question.  I would like to
