		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  We'll start with Bob Genetski,
president of Genetski Associates, on restructuring the
Tax Code and our financial markets.<p>

		Bob, thanks for coming.<p>

<a name="Genetski"></a><center>PRESENTATION BY BOB GENETSKI<br>
PRESIDENT, GENETSKI ASSOCIATES</center>
<p>
<center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>

<center>"Tax Restructuring and Financial Markets" </center>
<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  Okay.  Thanks.  <p>

		It's a pleasure to be here.<p>

		Okay.  Let me tell you, first of all, I'm going
to be talking primarily as an economist, but also I
can't help but to talk as a small businessman --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Right.<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  -- because I do have my own
company as well.<p>

		And as an economist, most of my work has been
associated with research on the tax system and its
effect on the economy, as well as on the tax system and
its effect on financial markets.<p>

		And I want to touch on three areas:  <p>

			One, the abuse in the current tax system.<p>

			Second, what should not be done in the way
of reform.<p>

			And third, what should be done in the way
of reform.<p>

		First of all, in terms of the current tax
system, there is no doubt that it's inefficient, it's
wasteful, it's destructive, it promotes abuse, and it
undermines family values.<p>

		It has got a lot of costs associated with it. 
Some are obvious, and they've been mentioned before. 
And some are not so obvious.<p>

		Among the fairly obvious costs are the costs of
compliance and administration.  And the figures there
are pretty astounding, about <p>

$150 billion, bare minimum, in terms of cost of
compliance and administration.<p>

		And if we divide that by the number of workers,
we're talking about $1200 per worker per year for the
current tax system.<p>

		That's an obvious cost.  Some of the costs are
less obvious.  They're indirect costs that result from
the type of inefficiencies promoted by the tax system
over time, because we don't get the productive
investment that we normally would have.<p>

		My estimate of what this costs is somewhere in
the vicinity of $5000 per worker for this year alone. 
So, you can see the costs are enormous.  And these are
just the beginning of the costs.  <p>

		There are also psychological costs to a tax
system that undermines moral feelings and moral values.<p>

		My wife and I have a couple of friends who are
fairly well off.  They have gotten a divorce strictly
for tax reasons.  They claim they save $60,000 a year
by not being married, and yet they still live together.<p>

		You don't have to be wealthy.  My son, my first
son to get married, got married a year ago and found
out, after doing some calculations, that just being
married, instead of living together, meant that the
modest incomes that he and his wife make were taxed at
an extra $700 in terms of income tax, simply because
they had decided to go ahead and get married.<p>

		Traditionally, I think we like to have a lot of
respect for our government.  When we see a tax system
doing what it's doing to us, a great deal of resentment
builds up.  And clearly this resentment is not healthy.<p>

		Actually, I think the resentment would run even
deeper if people really understood the full costs and
the full quirks in the current tax system and some of
the ridiculous things they do.<p>

		For example, in my work and research into the
effect of the tax system on financial markets, it's
very clear to me that there is a substantial premium
that is in most interest rates as a result of the
nature of the tax system.  <p>

		The tax deductibility of the interest, on one
hand, and the fact that the government taxes interest
payments, on the other, adds approximately one-third to
every taxable interest rate that we're looking at.  <p>

		So, one-third of the taxable rates that we're
looking at are strictly attributable to the current tax
system.<p>

		What does that mean for mortgages?  That means
that an 8 percent mortgage under a system that did not
artificially exempt interest expenses and tax interest
rates, the 8 percent mortgage should really be less
than <p>

5-1/2 percent.  And that's what would happen under
certain reforms of the tax system.<p>

		Another interesting thing is federal debt.  The
federal government pays approximately $210 billion a
year in interest on the debt.  One-third of that
interest results from the in the tax system, $70
billion.  <p>

		Now, there's an offset.  The government gets
money back and gets revenue back when people pay taxes
on their interest income.<p>

		But there's not a full offset for a lot of
people.  For example, foreigners, rich foreigners,
wealthy foreigners, foreign central banks, foreign
institutions, all get the full benefit of this tax
premium that results from our tax law.<p>

		I have calculated that that is a pure gift to
wealthy foreigners of more than <p>

$15 billion every year that most people simply don't
accept or don't understand that's involved in the
current complexity of our tax laws.<p>

		So, there is a lot of abuse for the current tax
system.  I think that just about everyone is aware of
that.  And the key question is:  How should we change
it?<p>

		It's a very critical question.  In my research,
I've found that tax policy is the single most important
factor affecting economic growth and affecting incomes. 
And the opportunity for tax reform doesn't come around
too often.<p>

		And so when we do get the opportunity, it's
absolutely critical to get it right.  And getting it
right means making sure we don't make mistakes and
undertake some type of reform that's at least as bad or
perhaps worse than the current system.<p>

		The first type of reform that I believe is
definitely worse than the current system would involve
a VAT, or a valued-added tax.  This type of tax is an
utter failure wherever it's imposed.  <p>

		It's extremely complex.  It's highly expensive. 
It penalized those who have saved in the past.  And
it's a hidden tax.  People don't realize exactly what
they're paying for their government.  <p>

		And when they don't realize how much they're
paying for their government, there's a tendency to
demand more government than they otherwise would get.<p>

		Another direction that we don't want to go
would be a national sales tax.  A national sales tax is
certainly simpler than the VAT, not as expensive, but
it has the disadvantage of hitting those who are least
able to pay the hardest.<p>

		And if we try and play with the sales tax to
avoid hurting low-income people, by exempting certain
items and trying to tax higher incomes at a higher
rate, we end up with all the complexities of the
current tax system.  So, that's certainly a nonstarter.<p>

		In addition, the sales tax has the same
disadvantages of the VAT, in the sense that it
penalizes anyone who has saved in the past, because
their income is worth less under the new, high cost for
all these items.<p>

		And secondly, the cost of government is hidden. 
It's not obvious to people.  If you hide the cost of
government, people are going to demand more government
than they otherwise would.<p>

		Third, we don't want to reform the tax system
and keep the current high marginal tax rates.  And my
reason for this third point relates directly to some of
the research I have done on the effects of taxes on
economic activity.<p>

		What I have found is that taxes are a very
powerful force affecting economic activity.  Most of my
work has been devoted to something that I call the
effective marginal tax rate paid by upper-income
individuals, individuals in the 70th to 95th
percentile.  The effective marginal rate is the rate
they actually pay to the government after all the
deductions and everything else.<p>

		Looking at this rate historically, I have found
that for every one percentage point change in this
effective marginal tax rate, productivity growth in the
economy changes by roughly 2/10ths of a percent in the
opposite direction.  <p>

		Now, this doesn't sound like a whole lot, but
you add productivity changes up, and they accumulate
over years, and before you know it, you're talking
about very significant increases in living standards as
a result of this particular tax policy.<p>

		So, my conclusion with this respect is that we
don't want to raise or even keep marginal tax rates the
same.  <p>

		As a matter of fact, this research incidentally
suggests that when you go back historically, whenever
effective marginal tax rates were changed, it was
usually associated -- almost always associated with a
tax increase.  And the same was true whenever effective
marginal tax rates were cut.<p>

		The one example we have of lowering effective
marginal tax rates during the 1986 Tax Act, but trying
to balance it by raising taxes in other areas and
cutting off deductions, suggests that we do not the
same impact on productivity rule.  <p>

		As a result, if you really want positive impact
on the economy, it can't simply be a tradeoff of
lowering marginal rates and raising rates somewhere
else.  <p>

		The maximum amount of tradeoff is going to come
from lowering the rates, not only at the margin but
also on average, trying to get them down as low as
possible.<p>

		What should we do?  <p>

		In concept, the technical features of an ideal
tax have already been worked out by Hall and Rabushka
in their book "The Flat Tax."  They've done a lot of
work, over a decade of serious thinking.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Bob, with all due respect,
they're going to testify.  <p>

		We're going to spend three days with Rabushka
and --<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  Okay.  And let me just say one
thing about the Hall and Rabushka plan and also the
other plan.  The plan is a great plan.  <p>

		As a small business person, who looks at this,
also, from a business perspective, I believe that they
made a mistake in terms of their treatment of the
payroll tax.  And that's extremely important,
especially in light of some of the test -- <p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Can we do that in Q&amp;A?  I want
to get to the other --<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  Sure.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  -- testimony and get some
interface --<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  Sure.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  -- with the Commission.<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  Okay.  Can I just make one last
point --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Absolutely.<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  -- just very quickly, on
something that was brought up earlier, because the main
objective, as I see it, of this Commission is going to
have to be to sell the public, first, on the abuses in
the system and, second, on the benefits that can be had
from the ideal tax --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Right.<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  -- the flat tax.<p>

		In terms of doing that, you can be as eloquent
as you possibly can, the written report, my belief is
that unfortunately today too many people don't read,
and they just don't pay any attention to that. <p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  What would you suggest?<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  What I would suggest is the
panels that you're listening to, the passion that you
saw in the earlier panels today -- <p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Right.<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  -- you've already got some
videotapes of that.  <p>

		If that can be put together in a half-hour or
an hour show, showing real people, the problems they've
encountered, and letting people know what in the heck
the problems are, and then quickly some vignettes on
some of the ideal solutions, I think that that would go
a long way to --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>   Good.  Thank you.  		
Thank you, Bob.<p>

		Patrick Hendershott, Pat Hendershott --
Professor Hendershott if Ohio State University <p>

-- thank you for coming.<p>

<a name="Hendershott"></a><center>PRESENTATION BY PATRICK HENDERSHOTT<br>
OHIO STATE UNIVERSITY</center>
<p><center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>


<center>"Tax Reform and Housing"</center>
<p>

		<b>MR. HENDERSHOTT:</b>  Thank you for inviting me and
giving me the chance to see the fair city of Omaha.<p>

		It is a pleasure, again, to be of potential
service to Mr. Kemp.  He may not remember, but I was
the chief outside consultant for Price Waterhouse when
they did their first actual review of FHA back in '89,
'90.  And at that time, you were able to take steps to
help save FHA.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Thank you.<p>

		<b>MR. HENDERSHOTT:</b>  I hope the Commission will be
able to take steps to help save the future of my
granddaughters and other grandchildren in America.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Good.<p>

		<b>MR. HENDERSHOTT:</b>  Today is a particularly
appropriate day to have me on to talk about housing,
because there's an Op-Ed piece that you may or may not
have seen in the Wall Street Journal this morning by
Bruce Bartlett, titled "Will the Flat Tax KO Housing?"<p>

		As always, Mr. Bartlett says many interesting
things, but I'm afraid he isn't always entirely
correct.  And that's really -- it turns out that's
really the topic of my conversation this morning.<p>

		All investments -- virtually all investments
pay two kinds of returns.  They pay sort of a periodic
cash flow.  Stocks pay dividends, interest. 
Investments in real estate will pay various kinds of
net rents, and most investments will pay capital gains.<p>

		Now, owner-occupied housing is just like these
other investments.  Owner-occupied housing has a cash
flow return.  This cash flow return is the rents that
the occupier pays himself as the owner.  The implicit
rents are on owner-occupied housing.  That's the cash
flow.  Of course, in housing, you generally get capital
gains.<p>

		The tax advantage for owner-occupied housing is
the very light taxation of these returns.  We don't tax
the implicit rents on housing; and we tax the capital
gains at a very low rate, due to deferrals and the
like.<p>

		I could stop at that point, and I could tell
you that's the tax advantage to owner-occupied housing. 
Note that I have not mentioned the mortgage interest
deduction.<p>

		Due to my hard work, clean living, and mainly
aging and having a frugal wife, I have accumulated
significant wealth, so I don't have a mortgage on my
house.  It makes -- there's no advantage for me to have
a mortgage on my house. 		You could imagine me
getting a mortgage, investing it in Ginnie Mae
securities, the same kind of investment, a mortgage.  I
earn interest on the mortgage investments.  I pay taxes
on it.  I write off the mortgage interest as a tax
deduction.  It's a wash.  A mortgage interest deduction
doesn't give me a tax advantage.  The tax advantage is
the virtual nontaxation of the return from the asset.<p>

		Now, what role does the mortgage interest play? 
The mortgage interest deduction says that not only do I
get the tax advantage from owner-occupied housing, but
my children do.  My children are young.  They don't
have wealth.  They have to borrow.<p>

		What the mortgage interest deduction says is
that there will not be a penalty to debt financing of
housing.  The mortgage interest deduction does not give
a tax advantage to debt.  I have already shown that it
doesn't give me any advantage.  <p>

		The tax advantage, what the mortgage interest
deduction does is it says that young people will have
the tax advantage just as well as older people.  It
levels the playing field; it doesn't make in unlevel.<p>

		So, what would you do if you took away the
mortgage interest deduction?  When you take away the
mortgage interest deduction, you create an unlevel
playing field, you buy deficit financing of housing in
favor of equity, and you basically are going to cause a
redistribution of income.<p>

		Now, this isn't a redistribution between income
classes.  We know that the vast majority of the
advantage of the mortgage interest deduction goes to
higher-income people, but they pay most of the taxes. 
So, that's not going to cause any -- the redistribution
is from young to old.  <p>

		We take away the mortgage interest deduction,
we can use the revenue to lower taxes.<p>

		People like myself will get a tax break. 
People like my kids will get a tax break, but they'll
more than pay for it by not being able to deduct the
mortgage interest.  <p>

		So, to remove the mortgage interest deduction
would create a redistribution from young to old people,
and you, as the Commissioners, I am certain, know.<p>

		Now, one of our major problems is we've been
doing these kind of redistributions for the last two
decades, intentionally by raising real Social Security
benefits, unintentionally raising them through mixups
in the CPI in '82 and other things.  <p>

		We have been transferring resources from young
to the old.  We don't need to do any more of that.<p>

		I've got some more things on my sheet, but I
know we don't have any time, so I'll stop.  		
Thank you very much. 	<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Caught me by surprise, you
know.<p>

		<b>MR. HENDERSHOTT:</b>  Good.  Good.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		Good.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Such pithy testimony.<p>

		George Zodrow, chairman of the Economics
Department at Rice University.<p>

		George, thank you for coming.<p>

<a name="Zodrow"></a><center>PRESENTATION BY GEORGE ZODROW<br>
CHAIRMAN, ECONOMICS DEPARTMENT AT RICE UNIVERSITY</center>
<p>
<center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>

<center>	"Comparison of Alternative Plans<p>

and Some Options"</center>
<p>

		<b>MR. ZODROW:</b>:  Thank you very much for inviting
me.  It's my pleasure to be here.<p>

		In my comments, what I'd like to do is discuss
briefly some general principles that economists use in
thinking about tax reform and how some of the various
consumption tax proposals that are out there stack up
against the current income tax in terms of those
criteria; and then also comment briefly on some general
outlines about the three plans that are out there. 
There are some things that you might think about in
reviewing these various proposals.<p>

		Let me begin by noting that there is fairly
widespread, although certainly not unanimous by any
means, agreement among academic economists and, I
think, business economists as well that consumption
taxes meet, generally speaking, the goals of a tax
system more -- they meet it better than an income tax
would, especially our current income tax.<p>

		The first of these goals really is the focus of
this Commission.  And that's the positive effects on
savings, capital formation, economic growth that a
consumption tax system might give rise to, as well as
the associated increases in economic efficiency that
would come from uniform taxation of both investment and
savings.  <p>

		It seems likely that a consumption<p>

based reform would result in some additional savings
and some additional growth, but I should warn you --
and I am sure this will come out in the hearings --
that there is a fair amount of disagreement as to
exactly how large this effect would be.  <p>

		So, I think it's important to think about the
other advantages of consumption taxation as well.<p>

		The second goal is fairness.  The basic
argument here, I think, is just that double taxation of
savings is unfair.  This has been refined in various
ways, but that's the nuts and bolts of it.<p>

		But there are a couple of other dimensions that
I think you have to worry about.  		One is the
obvious one, making the changes big, is that moving to
a consumption tax is going to be complicated if it is
accompanied by a redistribution of the tax burden from
the middle-class, upper-income people. <p>

		And so whether or not you think that's fair I
think is an open issue.  But I think it does complicate
the mix if you have estimates of redistribution
occurring.<p>

		The second is a transitional issue, which is
that any consumption-based tax is going to pretty
favorable to capital owners.  And so it's important, in
thinking about the design, to try to make that
favoritism apply only to new capital and new savings to
the extent possible, and thus try to avoid granting
windfall gains to existing capital owners.<p>

		The third goal of tax reform, I think, would be
just simplicity.  And in my view, this is the most
compelling argument for a consumption tax.  <p>

		Here I really don't refer to the flatness of
the tax, but rather just the calculation of the base,
both at the business level and at the individual level. 
<p>

		There are just a lot of ways in which a
consumption base is inherently simpler than an income
tax base.  The most obvious ones are because it
eliminates issues of timing, it eliminates issues of
inflation accounting.  At the individual level, taxes
are much simpler.<p>

		There are a lot of other ways that one argue
this point, but I think it's an important one to keep
in mind.<p>

		Next, comparison of the three approaches that
are most commonly discussed.  The most obvious would be
a national retail sales tax, the type that's being
advocated by Senator Lugar and Congressman Archer.<p>

		Until recently, I would say that this was not
viewed seriously as a replacement for an income tax,
but it seems to be getting some additional attention. 
The problems primarily are it's very difficult, as Bob
mentioned, to try to get any element of progressivity
into the system.  <p>

		And it's difficult to exempt the purchases of
the poor.  If you start doing so, you basically start
messing up the system.  You start losing the simplicity
that you're striving for.<p>

		Another big difficulty is that a national
retail sales tax, if combined with a state and local
sales tax, is going to give you rates around 30
percent.  <p>

		Presumably you've got everything focused on
that one transaction.  That gives you a lot of
incentives for avoidance.  <p>

		And I think what might happen is that the
monitoring and enforcement efforts that would be
involved could be just as bad as they are and just as
intrusive as they are under the current income tax. <p>

		Finally, the practice now, in terms of the
sales tax, is not too encouraging in that most
estimates suggest that businesses end up paying as much
as 50 percent of the so-called retail sales tax.  If
you do that, you're really losing almost all the
economic advantages of taxation on the basis of
consumption.<p>

		The second approach is typified by the Nunn-Domenici plan, but more generally is just referred to
as a cash flow tax.  There's sort of obviously a tax on
consumption in the sense that you get a deduction for
saving when your withdrawals are taxed, both the
principal and interest if they're consumed.  <p>

		It's a very elegant approach to consumption
taxes.  It has the advantages of being consistent with
some well-known features of the current law, IRAs,
401(k) plans, and such.  And it also appears to be
taxing capital income, although, in fact, not much of
that really happens.<p>

		But the main problem I think with Nunn-Domenici
is it just so complicated, and there are a variety of
schemes that could be used to avoid taxes or at least
defer them for long periods of time.<p>

		The other aspect of it is if you look at the
combined business and individual-level taxes, the top
rate approaches -- the combined rate is like 50
percent.  And I think, in terms of incentives, that's
something one would want to worry about considerably.<p>

		The last approach would be what's referred to
in the economic literature as a tax prepayment
approach, which is more commonly called the Armey or
the Hall-Rabushka flat tax.<p>

		I think it's the simplest approach.  It's
called a consumption tax because the tax burden is
similar, in present value terms, to what would arise
under an obvious consumption tax, even though it looks
more like a tax base they put on wage income and on
pension distributions. <p>

		Since it is an individually based tax, though,
it's easy to make it as progressive as you want.  And
it's easy to exclude low-income individuals from
paying, if that's what you wish to do, as well.<p>

		There is a very interesting problem with this
approach though, and that is that most economic
analyses of a Hall-Rabushka or an <p>

Armey-type plan suggest that the individual cash flow
alternative would lead to much bigger increases in
savings and much bigger increases in economic welfare.<p>

		This happens for two reasons.<p>

		First, under a cash flow tax, you've got to
save more, because you've got to anticipate paying
those future taxes.  <p>

		Now, that can be offset under an Armey plan,
but in order for that to happen, the government has to
save more.  But it just has to use the revenues it gets
earlier and use those to reduce deficits.  Some people
are understandably skeptical that that would happen.<p>

		The second issue is something which Bob alluded
to, and that is under a cash flow approach, effectively
what happens is you have a one-time hit on the owners
of existing assets, typically viewed to be the older
elements of the population.  <p>

		What that means is that you can use those
revenues to reduce future tax rates.  And also, because
you're redistributing from the old -- you know,
speaking in general terms, from the old, who tend to be
consuming, to the young, who are in the savings
portions of their life cycle, you have another impetus
to saving.<p>

		So, both of these tend to give you pretty big
effects under a cash flow approach, which you don't get
under Hall-Rabushka.<p>

		What the latter suggests, I suppose, is that
you want to worry a bit about under the Hall-Rabushka
or Armey plan, about trying to avoid giving a windfall
gain to the elderly or to owners of existing capital
assets, because basically what you do is you'd say,
well, let's forgive expected future taxes on capital
income.  So, you're redistributing income in the other
direction.<p>

		One final point on that issue is just to -- I'm
sure this will come up in the hearings -- is some
people are actually advocating a cash flow approach,
but for this reason.  <p>

		In other words, they're saying, "Well, it's a
good thing to impose a windfall tax on the elderly,
because it reverses some of the effects of the other
fiscal policies that Pat mentioned that have
redistributed income from the younger generations to
older generations.<p>

		I see I'm running out of time.  I'll make one
final point -- <p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  I want to save a half-hour for
questions, so --<p>

		<b>MR. ZODROW:</b>:  Okay.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  We've still got John Anderson.  <p>

		Let me just wrap it up.<p>

		<b>MR. ZODROW:</b>:  Okay.<p>

		Well, why don't I just stop there.  And I'll
leave it --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  You can also use the time on
the questioning.<p>

		<b>MR. ZODROW:</b>:  Sure.  I'll do that.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Thank you very much, Professor
Zodrow.<p>

		John Anderson is professor of economics at the
University of Nebraska.<p>

		Welcome, Professor.  Glad to have you.<p>
  <a name="Anderson"></a><center>PRESENTATION BY JOHN ANDERSON<br>
PROFESSOR OF ECONOMICS UNIVERSITY OF NEBRASKA</center>
<p>
<center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>


<center>"State taxation"</center>
<p>

		<b>MR. ANDERSON:</b>  Thank you.    <p>

		Welcome to Nebraska.<p>

		I'd like to comment briefly on the effects and
potential implIcations for state and local governments
--<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Good.<p>

		<b>MR. ANDERSON:</b> -- from a federal tax reform.  <p>

		With some experience in the state and local
arena, I'd like to think through some issue with you
about what might happen if there is a federal reform
and how states are likely to respond.<p>

		Secondly, I'll address the issue of the
potential effects on state and local governments
bending and, finally, say some things about the effects
on the portfolio of taxes that state and local
governments have and how it might be altered with
federal reform.<p>

		First of all, what's the likely effect on state
governments, in terms of how they finance local public
goods and services?<p>

		Well, I think it's pretty clear that states
will generally conform to the federal base changes that
occur.  And I think we can draw on some experience from
the Tax Reform Act of 1986, to see that that's going to
happen.<p>

		States generally moved in the direction of
adapting their income taxes, those that have an income
tax, to the federal base definition.  They vary in
deductions, exemptions, credits, and rate structure, of
course.  But, by and large, states conformed to the
federal definition of "adjusted gross income."		<p>

		If we move in the direction of some kind of
consumption-based tax at the federal level, the
incentive will be there for states to conform to the
base definition, if not the credits and deductions and
exemptions and so on.  At least for the purposes of
defining the base, they're likely to begin with the
federal definition of the base.<p>

		That means that states would have the ability
to define differently the progressivity or regressivity
of their state tax based on how they set deductions,
exemptions, and what kind of credit mechanisms they
might attach to that base.  <p>

		They might have to worry about location effects
and other factors as a result, but it doesn't lock the
states into identical tax systems necessarily.<p>

		Secondly, there are some issues of
deductibility that have to be thought through.<p>

		The current situation on the income tax, where
we've got income and property taxes deductible on the
federal income tax, but sales taxes are not deductible,
is clearly an uneasy compromise between two competing
views of what should happen with deductibility.  <p>

		And a major reform ought to think that through
a little bit more carefully and decide which way to go,
either allow deductibility of all state and local taxes
or disallow them.  <p>

		Perhaps, if you're interested, we can talk
about the relative arguments on both sides of that. 
But the current situation is an uneasy one, where we're
trying to mix two views on deductibility with our
current nondeductibility of sales taxes.<p>

		And secondly, let me say, related to the
deductibility, that a tax reform that lowers marginal
tax rates, of course, reduces the impact of
deductibility in any case.  It doesn't take away the
problem, but it reduces the impact that deductibility
has. <p>

		Deductibility really reduces the differences in
tax prices that are paid across locations for state and
local public goods and services.  <p>

		And a tax reform that eliminates or reduces
deductibility will have the impact of exaggerating
price differences across communities, and that has
clear implications that you may want to think through.<p>

		Finally, related to the federal tax reform and
likely responses from states is the question of
windfall revenues if there is base broadening in any
sense.  We worried about that with the Tax Reform Act
of '86.  We saw what happened.  <p>

		And by and large, there was significant
political pressure to avoid collecting windfalls.  So,
I would presume there would be a similar outcome in
this case.  <p>

		If there's significant base-broadening, the
states are likely to be sensitive to that and avoid
collecting large windfalls.<p>

		What are the effects on state and local
government spending?  Well, here I think the context is
important to think about.  <p>

		Reform of the tax system is being considered
here amid very dramatic changes that are taking place
with respect to federal grant programs as well.  And
the design of the grant mechanisms can greatly affect
state and local spending behavior.  <p>

		Block grants that come have only income
effects.  Matching grants, of course, have both price
effects, substitution effects, as well as income
effects.<p>

		And so what needs to be done is to think
through carefully the combination of a tax reform and a
restructuring of the federal grant system and sending
money back to state and local governments.<p>

		Lower marginal tax rates at the federal level,
together with the potential loss of deductibility,
might raise the tax price for state and local public
goods and result in reduced demand for those goods. 
But the outcome depends crucially on what happens with
redesigning federal grant systems as well. <p>

		Let me conclude by saying there may be effects
on the tax portfolio of state and local governments. 
The long-term trend has been away from property taxes
at the state and local level, especially at the local
level, and toward income and sales taxes.<p>

		Federal tax reform can have direct effects on
the portfolio of revenue sources that state and local
governments rely on.  It may further encourage that
long-term trend, or it may encourage a different
direction.  <p>

		Federal tax reform can also have indirect
effects on tax arbitrage mechanisms on the portfolios
of state and local governments and have an impact that
way as well. <p>

		Well, let me stop there and --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Thank you.<p>

		<b>MR. ANDERSON:</b>  -- see what questions you may
have.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Thank you.  That's a good place
to turn to Matt Fong, Treasurer of the State of
California.<p>

		Mr. Fong. <p>

		COMMISSIONER FONG:  I'd like to follow up on
some of the state and local issues. California and
other states as well rely principally on a lot
municipal financing to do their infrastructure.<p>

		What impact do you think there would be if we
eliminated the difference between the taxable and the
nontaxable as we are trying to do infrastructure? <p>

		PARTICIPANT:  Well, to the extent that we
reduce marginal tax rates, we would expect the
differential between the taxable and the nontaxable
issues to shrink. <p>

		The question is whether that shrinking by
itself has important implications.<p>

		A tax reform that also has the impact of
stimulating savings might be expected to lower interest
rates in general.  <p>

		And so we're talking about thinking about two
different effects here:  	<p>

		How would tax reform affect the overall level
of interest rates?  <p>

		And how would it affect the differential
between taxable issues and nontaxable issues?<p>

		And the combination of the two things going on
at the same time is quite complex.  But there's no
question if you're moving in the direction of lower
marginal rates, you'd expect the differential to
shrink.  <p>

		That means, for a municipality, that the price
of activity relative to what it would take to go out
and borrow at taxable rates goes up.  So, it becomes
more expensive for municipalities to fund their
projects. <p>

		On the other hand, there may be an impact on
interest rates overall that works in the opposite
direction.  <p>

		And some of the other panelists could certainly
comment on that as well.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Ted.<p>

		MR. FORSTMANN:  Yes.  I wanted to ask a couple
of questions of Professor Hendershott if I could.<p>

		I listened pretty carefully to it,  because I
think this something that's going to come up.  And I
got a little lost, because -- and I have three things
to say here.  <p>

		You were saying that if this deduction were
done away with that equity would be favored or promoted
over debt.  <p>

		But my first question would be -- and maybe
I'll ask them -- all three at the same time.<p>

		My first question would be:  Well, without
arguing that point, isn't debt favored over equity now? 
<p>

		If you're going to get a tax benefit from doing
something in a particular way, you're using debt and
you don't get one from equity, isn't debt favored over
equity now?  And what's good about that?  Number one.<p>

		Number two.  If interest rates are going to
decline by a third, why can't your -- you know, why
can't the young person -- he doesn't get the deduction,
but he pays less for his loan, so why -- what's the
difference?  I don't see the difference.<p>

		So -- and if I'm right, then you must disagree
with Mr. Genetski, that the interest rate is going to
decline.<p>

		And lastly, even if you can answer the first
two questions, when you hear these kinds of horror
stories that you heard today from people -- and we've
been hearing and hearing and hearing, and we'll hear
more of -- and you realize that we've got, you know, a
huge problem to deal with here.<p>

		So even if the first two questions can't be
answered and we are going to favor the elderly over the
young, and we're going to favor equity over debt, and
we're going to do all that stuff relative to what we're
trying to accomplish, if you take the position that if
you allow one -- if you go to some flatter thing and
you allow one deduction to get in, and you know that if
you allow one to get in, the next thing, number two, is
going to show up, and then number three is going to
show up, and you're going to be back where you started,
is it all that important, relative to what we're trying
to accomplish here?<p>

		<b>MR. HENDERSHOTT:</b>  Well, I think there are a lot
of ifs here.  I want to -- but there is one factual or
conceptual issue that you raised, and that is:  Is debt
currently favored relative to equity?<p>

		Now, if you look at the taxation of
corporations, debt is favored relative to equity.  They
get to deduct their interest payments, but they don't
deduct their dividend payments.  And they're paying
taxes on income.<p>

		The difference with owner-occupied housing is
there is no tax on income.  There's no tax on income. 
And for people who equity finance, there's no write-off.  But why write off as long as there isn't a tax? <p>

		But when you talk about debt -- I mean,
basically people like myself are able to invest in
owner-occupied housing and earn a pretax return, a
nontaxable return, and we fund at a pretax cost.  It's
the opportunity cost, the cost of funds.<p>

		But if I invest with debt financing, I earn a
pretax rate of return, but I have to pay this under
current law -- under current law, I get to deduct the
interest, so I finance it with an after-tax yield.  And
the same thing is true if I finance it with equity.<p>

		My opportunity cost to investing my equity in
the house is to invest it in bonds or something where I
would be taxed.  <p>

		So, the opportunity cost of equity financing is
an after-tax yield.  The opportunity cost of debt
financing is an <p>

after-tax cost.  Those are equal.  That's a fair
system, a neutral system.  Take away the mortgage
interest deduction, it won't be neutral anymore.<p>

		Now, we might have to do this again sometime.<p>

		Your other points -- you know, I truly believe
that if we went to a -- if we lower tax rates a lot --
of course, if we lower tax rates a lot, the value of
the mortgage interest deduction goes down also.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Right.<p>

		<b>MR. HENDERSHOTT:</b>  I truly believe if we lower
tax rates, that interest rates will go down.  I don't
believe they're going to go down as much as some other
people might argue.<p>

		There is an alternative view, and that is that
we have world capital markets.  And, in effect, then
the world sets our interest rates.  So, what the hell,
it doesn't make any difference.<p>

		I don't accept that view, but I don't accept
the -- I mean, I've done research myself that suggests
that tax rates do get built into interest rates.  But I
don't think -- they aren't going to fall that much. 
But they will fall.<p>

		Regarding these horror stories -- all right,
the last thing -- you know, we're obviously -- or
you're starting to argue about third best, fourth best. 
<p>

		You know, we can't do things exactly right,
but, no, it certainly is true that there is a -- that
taking away the home mortgage interest deduction,
combined with some other things, might be a good idea. 
I won't deny that.  <p>

		My basic point is that, on its face, taking
away the mortgage interest deduction doesn't make
sense.  <p>

		And if you don't like the tax advantage that
owner-occupied housing has, you should try and get rid
of it some other way.  <p>

		One other way is, of course, lower tax rates,
which means the relative advantage to owner-occupied
housing goes down.  You can take away the property tax
deduction, which I think is a fine idea.  <p>

		You could generally tax other investments less,
like the '81 Tax Act did.  I mean, you can do a lot of
things to take it away.  I don't think the mortgage
interest deduction is the right, but that's --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  I don't think you and Mr.
Forstmann are all that far off, because you keep
mentioning the marginal tax rate, and the value of the
exemption or deduction or credit goes down relative to
the reduction of the marginal rate.<p>

		What Mr. Forstmann is getting at, if I can be
so bold, is that if we are to get the rates as low as
we possibly can, and reduce the amount of not only
social engineering in the Code but also remove the tax
consequence of investment and saving and income-producing decisions, then I think he is on to
something; that once, if you get the rates as low as
you can, you've got to be careful that you don't start
adding back the problems that will complicate and
frustrate and exacerbate and add all the barriers to
productive economic activity.  <p>

		So, again, we're not prejudging the outcome,
but I think every man and woman on this panel wants to
find a way, within reason, in a political world, to get
the rates on productive human economic activity, i.e.,
working, saving, investing, and engaging in
entrepreneurial <p>

risk-taking -- want to get the rates as low as
possible, get the barriers removed, and let this
country explode into the 21st century.<p>

		John Wieland might have a sympathetic question.<p>

		MR. WIELAND:  Might I just add something?  If
you want to take away the mortgage interest deduction
for second and third homes, you know, that's fine.  But
I think the mortgage interest deduction in our current
Tax Code is a neutrality, rather than a glare.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Well, wait, wait, wait, wait. 
The current Tax Code stinks.  We are here to reform it
and change it and write a new one.  So --<p>

		MR. WIELAND:  I know.  I'm saying this aspect
of the current Tax Code is an appropriate aspect, given
the rest of the Code.  <p>

		And if you stick with the current Code, even if
you can --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  In the current Code --<p>

		MR. WIELAND:  -- lower tax rates to the point --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  In the current Code, the
interest deduction on a mortgage is sacrosanct --
sacrosanct.  It is sacred.<p>

		MR. WIELAND:  Well --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  I'm the Housing Secretary.  <p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		But we're not here --<p>

		MR. WIELAND:  You were the Housing --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  -- to defend the status quo.  <p>

		Reagan used to say, "'Status quo" is a Latin
phrase for the mess we're in."'  <p>

		And we're in a mess.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		We're going to get out of it.<p>

		So, Mr. Wieland.<p>

		MR. WIELAND:  Dr. Hendershott, I like your
analysis.  <p>

		I have two questions at this point.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Disputatious Commissioner.<p>

		MR. WIELAND:  The first is I would assume that
young people don't need really big houses.  So, if
we're going to, you know, eliminate this transfer from
the young to the old, you know, you said second homes
wouldn't need to be protected.  What caps would you
set, or would you set caps?	<p>

		<b>MR. HENDERSHOTT:</b>  I'm not sure that I would set
any caps at all.  <p>

		I think we -- I mean, young -- I mean, you
mentioned that young households don't need big houses. 
Well, nobody needs a big house.  		We're talking
about people being able to consume the resources they
have.  There may be some very-high-income young people
who should be having big houses, and they're going to
have to fund it with a lot of debt.  <p>

		When you start putting caps on, you're really -- you're trying to change the distribution of taxes in
the U.S. is what you're basically trying to do.  <p>

		And if you think that young people -- or,
excuse me, if you think that high-income people don't
pay enough taxes, you ought to tax them more heavily. 
I'm not sure the way to do it is to cap their interest
deduction.  So, I would not put caps on.<p>

		MR. WIELAND:  Second question.  First of all,
I'd like to say that you were described to me as the
best housing economist in the United States.  So, I
value your insights --<p>

		<b>MR. HENDERSHOTT:</b>  Well, I'd like to know who
the -- who made that statement.  I would send them a
Christmas card.<p>

		MR. WIELAND:  If people were convinced that the
mortgage interest deduction should go, what thoughts
would you have as to the transition aspects of people
who presently have mortgages?<p>

		<b>MR. HENDERSHOTT:</b>  That is a tough question that
I haven't thought a lot about.  There ought to be some
transitional thing.  I would certainly worry about
that. <p>

		On the other hand, if interest rates are going
to fall, you need less transition.  And also, there are
a number of people who probably, if you took away their
mortgage interest deduction, would find ways to have a
smaller mortgage.  <p>

		They currently have marketable assets they
could use to pay off their other mortgages, but there
just isn't an incentive under today's Tax Code.  <p>

		I can't -- I'll be glad to think about that,
but I don't want to answer it.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  We asked some of the people in
the audience if they would like to ask a question.  <p>

		And so any one of you --<p>

		Let me just make a couple of questions on their
behalf, and then treat it any way you possibly can.<p>

		First of all, from Rosalie Shepherd (phonetic),
not a question but a comment.  She is the director of
United We Stand America -- here in Nebraska I assume.  <p>

		And she wants us all to come to the national
conference in Dallas from August 11th to the 13th,
where this will be a main topic of the United We Stand
America people.  <p>

		They've got Bob Dole, Newt Gingrich, Phil
Gramm, Dick Gephardt, and other top <p>

policy-makers and a lot of grassroots folks.<p>

		So that's a plug for -- Rosalie, you left off
your 1-800 number.  Ross would be very upset that you
left off the 1-800 number. <p>

		I think it's Don or Dan Bartley (phonetic). <p>

		PARTICIPANT:  Don.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Don.  <p>

		And this -- you addressed it a little bit, Bob
Genetski.<p>

		How do we remove the social engineering aspects
of the tax system?  How do we get the cleanest system
to raise revenue for government's legitimate functions
and not get into the social engineering that now is
implicit -- in some cases explicit -- in the Tax Code? <p>

		And as you're thinking about that, one of the
ways in '81 we tried to remove the poor from the Tax
Code and deal with the payroll tax, alluded to so
eloquently in our earlier panel, was the earned income
tax credit.<p>

		Take those two questions, social engineering
and removing the poor from the burden of the payroll
tax by increasing the earned income tax credit.  And,
of course, this is phased out.  It leads to a high
marginal rate at a certain point, so those are two
questions that can be addressed by the panel.<p>

		Thank you.<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  Yes.  And I think --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  That was just to get the name
of the -- Pat O'Malley (phonetic) from Tax Help asked
the question of how many values are destroyed by
phasing in and out of the earned income tax credit.<p>

		Go ahead, Bob.  Excuse me.<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  It seems to me that the Armey
bill deals with that in the simplest, most effective
way, by getting the tax down to a flat rate for
everyone; and then allowing for a significant
deduction, so that anyone making up to, say, $35,000
doesn't have to pay tax.  <p>

		And then the 17 percent starts to come in after
that, a family of four gets that.<p>

		That seems to be the most straightforward,
simplest way.  And everyone can understand what's
happening, and you do away with the social engineering
and the very high marginal tax rates associated with
people getting government benefits.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  George.<p>

		<b>MR. ZODROW:</b>:  Well, I'd just like to note that
as far as the earned income tax credit, is to relate it
to a comment that was made earlier.  The earned income
tax credit, I think, was instituted with all kinds of
good motives.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Yes.<p>

		<b>MR. ZODROW:</b>:  But one of the side effects has
been that it dramatically increases the marriage
penalties on low-income households.<p>

		Some of the marriage penalties -- you have to
set the example up right, but if you do, and then you
have the right people getting married, the marriage
penalties are just horrendous, especially relative to
the tax burdens that the family would pay.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  I'm glad that the motives were
not challenged, because I was one of the co-authors of
the earned income tax credit because I realized there
were so many low-income people moving into their first
job at Herman Cain's pizza factory --<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		-- or anyplace else faced a marginal tax rate
of unbelievable -- the highest rate of taxation in the
country was a low-income woman trying to take a job
with a child or two or a father who's unemployed who
takes his first job.<p>

		So, is the answer, Bob, to social engineering,
just get simplicity of a flatter, fairer, simpler,
lower rate system and then exempt the poor by using the
personnel exemption?<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  That would be my answer.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Yes.  Up to -- did you have a
question?<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  Well, follow-up to that.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Go, go.  You're on.<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  You started to mention earlier,
but you didn't get a chance, since you had mentioned
the flat tax, and you said that was a criticism that
you had of Hall-Rabushka.  <p>

		Could you comment on that --<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  Yes, yes.<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  -- since we are talking about
that?<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  Yes, the -- in <p>

Hall-Rabushka, they try to avoid dealing with the
payroll taxes, because that's a whole different ball
game from the income tax.  And you really chew up an
awful lot just in dealing with the income tax alone.<p>

		But they are forced to deal with it, because it
is such a big factor, and at least recommend how they
would incorporate dealing with the payroll tax into
their flat tax system.  And they've got two possible
ways of solving the problem. <p>

		One is to treat Social Security -- or the
payroll portion -- as a pension, allow business to
deduct the tax that business has to pay and then tax
the people who receive Social Security benefits.  <p>

		They chose not to do that.  They chose to treat
the payroll tax as if it were a fringe benefit, and
therefore not to allow business to deduct the payroll
tax, but then have people who receive the Social
Security benefits receive them tax-free.  <p>

		This, to me, is the wrong decisions for a
couple of reasons.<p>

		First, I believe it puts a tremendous
additional benefit or cost on businesses, when you
clearly have to pay this item out.  It's not like a
fringe benefit, where you can raise wages in return for
that.<p>

		Also -- and this is a very important point for
those who eventually believe and would like to see
Social Security changed along the lines it has been
done in Chile -- the more you treat the Social Security
system as a pension, it appears to me the easier it's
going to be to make that transition.  <p>

		The more you treat it as some sort of a fringe
benefit, I think the more difficult it's going to be to
achieve that.<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  Thank you.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Commissioner Kleckner.<p>

		COMMISSIONER KLECKNER:  For any of you, but
maybe Bob Geneski and George Zodrow, you commented
earlier -- well, all of you did -- on the -- maybe the
ease of taxation or the -- in my words, "a hidden tax
versus a hurting tax." <p>

		You know, tax withholding for income tax
reasons, you're either on salary, your tax is withheld,
all the employees' tax is withheld.  		Our
employees at American Farm Bureau, 100 or so that we
have, really don't know how much money -- they know
what they get in their check, but they don't know the
total that they get, compared to a small businessman or
a farmer that has to write that check once a year or
twice a year, or whatever.  So, we know it's hurting.  <p>

		Your views on hidden taxes versus hurting
taxes, which are more transparent.  And also the idea
of tax withholding.  <p>

		If Shirley Peterson were here -- and I know she
regretted she had to leave -- but the IRS perspective
is you've got to withhold or people can't pay or won't
pay.<p>

		I tend to agree with Shirley, but on this one,
heck, farmers pay all the time or we go to jail.  And
we pay by the 1st of March, not April 15th, mainly.<p>

		I wanted, when I became American Farm Bureau
president, to pay our employees just one check a year -- wanted to start out once every quarter, went to once
every six months, and once a year, give them their
whole check, and maybe even withhold some so that they
wouldn't have to get anything back.  <p>

		I proposed doing it in December, give them a
little extra check at Christmastime, or a bigger check,
whole check, and "This is what you're really earning
before all the withholding."  <p>

		I was told we couldn't do it.  It's illegal.  I
guess we'd have gone to jail if we had tried to do it.  <p>

		But the idea -- are we to the point where we
got to withhold or the whole tax structure of the
country collapses, IRS goes into orbit if we don't
withhold, because we'll all go to jail or not?  What do
you think?<p>

		Anybody?  <p>

		George.<p>

		<b>MR. ZODROW:</b>:  Well, I think the main advantage
of withholding is just a present value issue.  If
everybody were to wait until the end of the year, then
it just would be a matter of higher rates that would
have to be assessed in order to get the same present
value of revenues to the government.<p>

		In terms of the visibility of the taxes or the
extent to which the role that the tax structure plays
in terms of the overall level of government
expenditures, I don't think there's actually that much
difference between the various approaches.  <p>

		It's more a situation where, I think, that if
you were to, say, load up with the sales tax.  People
say the sales tax is hidden and for that reason it
would tend to lead to bigger government.  <p>

		If you had a sales tax, a national sales tax of
21, 22 percent; and you had state sales taxes, 5, 6, 8
percent; local taxes, maybe 1 or 2 percent on top of
that, people would notice that.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		That's not a tax which would be a hidden tax.<p>

		The same thing applies, I think, to income
taxes.  People sometime say that withholding is a means
of a hidden tax.  And I suppose there's some validity
to that.  But everyone has to fill out their tax
return, and everyone sees that bottom line.  And it's
hard to imagine, really, that that is that much of a
hidden tax.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  That's the question that
Richard <b>MR. SCHENKEN:</b> (phonetic), who's in our audience, asked
about, the visibility of the tax.<p>

		Bob, do you want to take a shot at this whole
question of transparency and visibility and --<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  Well, just as a <p>

general --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  -- can we keep the government
from demanding more and more and more?<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  I would say, just as a general
principle of good taxation, that the tax system,
whatever it is, should be a transparent as possible.  <p>

		Now, the problem is, is it going to end up
being more work, more time, more effort to have the
employee write out the check, send it to the
government?  Is that more paperwork?  And does it
really pay in the end?  Or to just have the employer
take it out? <p>

		One way or another, you're balancing
transparency with the costs, the additional costs
involved.  And I'm not sure the additional costs are
worthwhile.  But whatever tax system you come up with,
I think it should be as transparent as possible so that
people very obviously know what they're paying.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Pat, do you want to make a
comment on that?<p>

		<b>MR. HENDERSHOTT:</b>  Yes.  I think  withholding is
obviously here to stay.  But the thing I really object
to in the Tax Code, probably more than anything, is
this hidden marginal tax rate, where you're phasing out
the personal exemptions, the standard deduction.  What
a crock.  <p>

		I mean, to be able to argue that our marginal
tax rates are low and this is going on -- I mean, this
is just really -- <p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  We can put you down as a strong
view on that subject.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		<b>MR. ZODROW:</b>:  I don't feel strongly about that
though.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Yes, right.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		Well, that aroma that is weaving its way
through this room is that of the finest pizza --<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		-- in the Midwest.<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  In the world.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  The Western Judeo-Christian
civilization.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		Klaus Beck (phonetic), our last question, asked
something that I think is critical to our
deliberations.<p>

		Hypothetically now, once we get a new system --
again, big hypothesis -- I believe it can be done, and
I believe the '96 election will be fought out over
these issues.  Okay?  That's what we believe.  <p>

		That's why we're doing this work.  There isn't
anybody here who is getting anything personal out of
this.  We're not seeking anything.  We're not being
paid.  <p>

		But how do you lock it in?  How do we lock in
the principle that the government should raise
legitimate revenues efficiently, effectively, with the
least burden on the poor and those least able to bear
that burden, but not consume our income?  <p>

		How do we -- do we have a constitutional
amendment?  Do we have a national referendum?<p>

		What would be your advice -- real quick -- on
how to lock in -- as much as humanly, politically
possible -- a 21st century Tax Code for American?  <p>

		Any comments?<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  I'd say a super-majority to raise
taxes --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  In the Congress?	<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  In Congress or to -- and by
raising taxes, I mean increasing tax <p>

breaks --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Yes.<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  -- and all this kind of thing.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Dick Gephardt came out for a
national referendum.  I thought that was interesting. <p>

		John?  Or George?  Or Bob?<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  Well, let me just make one quick
comment, which is that the national referendum or the
super majority, or whatever it might be, I think really
should apply to issues of base.  <p>

		I think most people think in terms of rates,
and let's hold a cap on rates.  But rates presumably
are going to fluctuate, depending on international and
national conditions, and even taste regarding public
services.     <p>

		I think the critical feature here, though, is
the change in the base.  If you're successful in
getting a truly pure base, if you will, then that is
the item which I think you need to focus on in terms of
designing your super-majorities.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Bob.<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  Yes.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Any comment?  We're going to --<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  No, I'm not a big fan of
constitutional amendments.  I think we might have too
many.  I'd like to take the -- what is it, the
allowance of the income tax, 16th Amendment?  I'd like
to take that out.  But other than that, Congress has so
many ways of circumventing whatever amendment that you
put.<p>

		Just -- again, putting the burdens of whatever
it wants to do directly on business, instead of running
it through the tax system, has been their latest ploy.  <p>

		It's really a question of good will more than
anything else.  <p>

		And the one thing that happens, if you go to
the flat tax system, is you switch a heck of a lot of
power and influence away from Congress.<p>

		PARTICIPANTS:  Away from politicians?<p>

		<b>MR. GENETSKI:</b>  From politicians.  <p>

		And you're -- essentially -- and this is one of
the challenges -- you're asking those politicians to
give up something that they hold near and dear.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		And as a result of that, the arguments in favor
of a flat tax have to be overwhelming to overcome that
huge objection.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  I mentioned in the last hearing
-- in Boston, I think -- that a city councilman in Hong
Kong -- I made no secret of the fact that I had been an
admirer of the <p>

Hong Kong economic miracle.  The last city councilman
who advocated doing away with the <p>

15 percent flat income tax in Hong Kong lost his seat,
overwhelmingly.<p>

		Thanks for you being here, Bob, and Pat.  Thank
you, George, John.  Appreciate a view from the groves
of academe.<p>

		I would invite my fellow Commissioners to step
over to the podium.  We're going to do a little press
availability to let some of our friends in the press
get back at us after those vicious attacks, ad hominem
--<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		-- on the press.<p>

		And then we'll, at 12:30 sharp, have a pizza
lunch.<p>

		Thank you all for being here.<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  Thank you.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  And we appreciate the good
questions from our audience.<p>

		Thank you.<p>

		(Applause)<p>

		(Whereupon, at approximately 12:20 p.m., the NATIONAL COMMISSION ON ECONOMIC GROWTH
AND TAX REFORM PUBLIC HEARING was adjourned.)<p>
